<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0768 10-07 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0768,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighty AIDS Demonstrators Arrested at Federal Building Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with San Francisco protest. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, `Those arrested...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators blocked entrances to a federal
building on Friday, demanding that the government do more to fight
AIDS. Eighty protesters were arrested and five officers slightly
injured, authorities said.
   In San Francisco, at least 20 other demonstrators were arrested
in the city's predominantly gay Castro District after marching
there from a rally at the Federal Building two miles away.
   The protesters took over the intersection of Market and Castro
streets to demand a better coordinated national battle against
AIDS. They briefly struggled with dozens of police in riot gear,
according to broadcast reports. Police officials did not
immediately release information about the arrests.
   The Los Angeles demonstrators, numbering from 300 to 400,
carried placards and shouted, chanted and whistled as they
converged on the Federal Building shortly after dawn.
   Those arrested were charged with trespassing for blocking the
entrances to the building, said Mike Larson of the General Services
Administration.
   Seven demonstrators were also cited for resisting arrest and one
was arrested for investigation of assaulting a Federal Protective
Service Police officer after spitting in an officer's face, Larson
said.
   The injured officers suffered cuts and bruises, Larson said.
   Wendell Jones, a spokesman for AIDS Coalition to Unleash
Power-Los Angeles, accused the police of using excessive force.
   ``The police would take their knees and shove them into the
protesters' backs for no reason, except to inflict pain,'' he said.
   ``I have no reports of that,'' Larson said.
   Chip Suntheimer of Act Up-LA said the demonstrators were
demanding quicker release to the public of experimental drugs to
fight AIDS, establishment of an emergency program to wipe out AIDS,
an end to AIDS-related discrimination and quality health care for
all AIDS sufferers, including poor people and members of minority
groups.
</TEXT>
