<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast Bjt   10-07 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Asks Baker To Set Up Talks on Palestinian Delegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
offering assurances that Israel's peace plan is ``very alive,'' is
asking the Bush administration to help break a deadlock over
Mideast negotiations.
   Shamir made the move Friday after the Israeli cabinet rejected
by tie vote a Labor Party proposal to meet with Egypt on the touchy
issue of which Palestinian Arabs should participate in negotiations.
   The prime minister said Israel ``had not closed the door on the
peace process.'' In fact, Shamir said, ``the Israeli peace
initiative is very alive.''
   Shamir's request for U.S. diplomatic intervention was aired in
an interview with Israel television and elaborated in discussions
between U.S. and Israeli officials.
   He called on Secretary of State James A. Baker III to set up
talks with Egypt and Israel on the composition of a Palestinian
delegation.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak proposed last month that two
Palestinians deported by Israel during disorders on the West Bank
and in Gaza should be included. Shamir and his supporters objected.
   A U.S. official who demanded anonymity said Baker was
considering Shamir's request, as well as other ways to set up
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. The official insisted the peace
process was not at a dead end.
   ``We are working hard, and we are hopeful,'' he said.
   Baker spoke by telephone with Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens and Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmet Abdel-Meguid after the
cabinet vote.
   U.S. officials said the cabinet had not dealt with other issues
surrounding the negotiations and that the discussion was expected
to resume next week in Jerusalem.
   Baker, meanwhile, looked for openings for compromise.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher insisted Israel had
not rejected Mubarak's 10-point proposal.
   ``Our view is that the Israeli cabinet has held a full
discussion and neither accepted nor rejected the Egyptian ideas,''
he said.
   Mubarak had proposed the negotiations in Cairo between an
Israeli delegation and Palestinians, including the two deportees.
Deputy Prime Minister Shimon Peres and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, leading members of the Labor party, approved.
   Mubarak's approach would require Israel to concede in advance
that it should relinquish territory on the West Bank and in Gaza as
a basis for gaining peace with the Arabs. Again, Peres and Rabin
agreed.
   The Egyptian leader put his proposal forward after the Palestine
Liberation Organization declined to endorse a plan by Shamir to
hold elections among the 1.4 million Palestinian Arabs who live in
the territories.
   After Baker met last week in New York with Arens and
Abdel-Meguid, he called on the Israeli cabinet to decide how to
``move forward'' on the Shamir proposal. Otherwise, Baker said at a
news conference Friday, ``We will have to go back to the drawing
board.''
   But after the deadlock, U.S. officials said there was no reason
to start anew and that Baker would seek an accommodation between
the Shamir and Mubarak plans.
   ``Any conclusion that it's over because it didn't happen today
is just not right,'' Boucher said. ``I don't think the secretary
put any time limit on this.''
   Baker, he said, was not planning to go to the Middle East.
   Baker endorsed the Shamir plan after it was adopted by the
Israeli cabinet in May. He has also praised the 10 points unveiled
by Mubarak last month, but said they were no substitute for
Shamir's proposal.
   On a related subject, Boucher confirmed reports that Robert
Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, recently held two
additional meetings with a PLO official. However, he declined to
disclose what they talked about.
   The PLO news agency, WAFA, said the meetings concerned ``the
efforts under way and the positions of the different concerned
parties to realize a net gain in the peace process.''
   Pelletreau has been meeting in Carthage with PLO officials since
December. The State Department has given only skimpy reports of the
sessions.
</TEXT>
