<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--AerLingus-Iran     10-07 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Aer Lingus-Iran,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aer Lingus Pleads Guilty in Iran Arms Shipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aer Lingus Airlines agreed Friday to plead guilty
to illegally transporting aircraft parts to Iran and will pay $1
million in fines and court costs.
   According to a two-count criminal information, the carrier's
subsidiary, Aer Lingus Production Export, worked with a Miami
company, Dane Aircraft Inc., which falsified export documents.
   Aer Lingus, the national airline of Ireland, could have faced a
maximum $2 million fine if convicted of both charges.
   The plea agreement must be approved by U.S. District Judge
Stanley Marcus at an Oct. 25 sentencing hearing.
   U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said that between 1981 and 1987,
Aer Lingus illegally transported parts for Lockheed C-130 aircraft
for use by the Iranian air force, despite a ban on such trade by
the U.S. government.
   A second count says that Aer Lingus transported Boeing parts to
Iran Air, a commercial airline.
</TEXT>
