<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Asia 1stLd-Writethru   10-07 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Asia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0630,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede ROME</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope Begins Politically Sensitive Trip to Asia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with pope arriving in South Korea;
picks up 4th pvs, `The Asian...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II arrived in South
Korea Saturday to begin a 10-day pilgrimage to Asia that is
expected to focus on human rights and Catholic-Moslem relations.
   The pope's special Alitalia Boeing 747 landed in South Korea
after leaving Rome's Leonardo da Vinci airport and making a brief
refueling stop in Venice.
   In a sign of vastly improved Vatican-Soviet relations, the
Kremlin approved a flight plan that allowed the papal plane to fly
over the Soviet Union. China barred a papal overflight.
   The Asian trip, the 44th foreign pilgrimage of John Paul's
11-year papacy, raises several politically sensitive topics for the
pope.
   In Seoul, the pope is scheduled to address a religious meeting
that has taken up the issue of eventual reunification of North and
South Korea.
   His next stop is overwhelmingly Moslem Indonesia and a stop in
East Timor, a heavily Catholic island annexed by Indonesia after
its invasion of 1975.
   John Paul will also make a two-day stop in the Indian Ocean
island nation of Mauritius before returning to Rome Oct. 16.
   South Korean police and intelligence agencies were placed on top
alert for the pope's visit, his second to the country following a
major tour in 1984. National Police Headquarters in Seoul said a
special watch was being maintained for members of the ``Gray
Wolves,'' identified as an ultra-rightist Turkish underground group.
   In 1981, a Turkish man alleged to be a member of the Gray Wolves
shot the pope in St. Peter's Square.
   The pope came to address the closing of the 44th International
Eucharistic Congress, which has included discussions about eventual
reunification of North and South Korea.
   The Seoul government is extremely wary about efforts to reunite
the two Koreas, which are technically at war since no peace treaty
was signed at the end of the Korean War in 1953. On Thursday, a
dissident pastor who made a secret trip to North Korea for
reunification talks was sentenced to 10 years in prison for aiding
an enemy power.
   Church officials say a small group of Catholics from North Korea
were invited for the papal visit but are not expected to be allowed
to attend by their Communist government.
   In an article published Thursday by the Vatican newspaper
L'Osservatore Romano, South Korean Cardinal Stephen Kim described
the division of Korea as ``a symbol of a divided world that so
ardently desires peace and reconciliation.''
   After Seoul, the pope will spend five days touring Indonesia.
While the scope of the visit is to meet with the tiny minority of 5
million Catholics in the population of 175 million, John Paul is
expected to stress the need for good relations between Moslems and
Christians.
   The Indonesian stop has been clouded by a fury over East Timor.
   This week, Portuguese President Mario Soares called Indonesia
``dictatorial'' and accused the Indonesian government of
persecuting East Timor's Catholic population.
   ``I hope that his Holiness will carry the message he's always
carrying in defense of the oppressed and the victims of
persecution,'' Soares said.
   The Vatican has not recognized East Timor's annexation, and the
bishop of Timor is directly under the jurisdiction of the Vatican
and not a member of the Indonesian Bishops Conference.
   The Vatican newspaper said John Paul wanted to make the stop,
scheduled for only half a day, to comfort Catholics so ``harshly
tested.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
