<FIRST>r a PM-JuryCookbook     10-07 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jury Cookbook,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Come Up With Cookbook to Fight Boredom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the jurors thought the most
stimulating part of Sousa vs. Pensacola Christian College was the
cookbook they wrote during the trial.
   It was the perfect recipe for combatting the tedium of a recent
civil trial that dragged on for four weeks, with jurors often
leaving the courtroom while attorneys argued details.
   ``Every time there was an objection, there would be a 15 to
20-minute delay,'' juror Linda Kinchen said. ``And we couldn't talk
about the case, so we started talking about food.''
   The jurors began reading recipes in magazines and then brought
in recipes from home to share. Some even brought in samples of
their favorite dish.
   Eventually they started writing out their recipes in longhand
and categorizing them into groups such as appetizers, main dishes,
salads or desserts.
   The jury for the civil fraud case decided to call their book
``Courtroom Cooks 'n Crooks (We Steal Recipes).''
   Circuit Court Judge Robert Makemson was given a copy of the book
at the end of the trial.
   ``They probably got tired of talking about their grandchildren
so they thought of this,'' Makemson said. ``More power to them.''
</TEXT>
