<DOCNO> AP891007-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--AirportStrike     10-07 0117</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Airport Strike,0119</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technicians Strike at Manila Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airport communications and
maintenance technicians struck early today over demands for pay
increases, paralyzing domestic and international air traffic,
officials said.
   The 300-strong labor union stopped work at 4 a.m., leaving
Manila's Ninoy Aquino International Airport without navigational
aid and limited communication facilities, said airport manager
Eduardo Carrascoso.
   At least 60 domestic flights had been canceled and there were no
incoming flights, he said. Only three international flights were
able to take off.
   Carrascoso said the workers, who make $178 a month, were
demanding a $13.70 pay increase to match the salaries of air
traffic controllers. He said officials were negotiating with union
leaders.
</TEXT>
