<HEAD>Bush Wearing Finger Splint After Surgery</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will be wearing a splint on his
finger for a few weeks after a cyst that had become increasingly
bothersome was removed surgically, the White House says.
   ``All is well,'' Bush said as he emerged from Walter Reed Army
Medical Center on Friday. ``It was real minor,'' he told reporters
jovially as he brandished his right hand with a bandaged middle
finger.
   The White House said the 25-minute minor surgery was successful
and that the president should experience no long-term impairment.
Bush is left-handed.
   The president was given a local anesthetic for the operation and
was to be prescribed pain medication as needed. He was spending the
weekend at the presidential retreat at Camp David, Md.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush had eight
stiches to close the 1{-inch incision and would wear a splint on
the finger for two to three weeks.
   Col. Allen Smith, chief of hand surgery at Walter Reed,
performed the operation and will visit the White House for a
follow-up exam Tuesday.
   White House physician Burton Lee said it appeared the cyst,
which was undergoing a pathological exam, was benign.
   Doctors had drained the cyst May 10 when Bush underwent a
routine physical examination. Physicians said the cyst had been
present for several years and did not pose a medical problem for
the 65-year-old president.
</TEXT>
