<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDAudits     10-07 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Audits,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Auditors Question Rent Formulas; Allege More Favoritism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is paying millions of dollars a
year in excessive housing subsidies because of errors in the way it
sets rents for the projects, HUD auditors say.
   The auditors said in a report obtained Friday that overpayments
by the Department of Housing and Urban Development could be as high
as $39.1 million for just the tiny sample of rent areas studied.
   They said they couldn't project their findings to estimate
potential nationwide overpayments because the sites selected for
the audit were not chosen randomly. But the report urged department
officials to revisit the formula and to give HUD's regional
economists a greater role in setting rents.
   A second audit, sent to Congress this week, raises fresh charges
of favoritism in awarding rent subsidies and says such conduct was
allowed because of poor program accountability. Mismanagement and
political favoritism are the key subjects of congressional
investigations of HUD during the Reagan administration.
   For the rent study, HUD's inspector general reviewed 142 of the
2,755 areas for which the department sets fair-market rents for
subsidized housing. The report said that in 116 of those areas the
government was paying $39.1 million a year in excessive subsidies.
   In a smattering of areas, the auditors said, HUD might be paying
too little.
   ``Increased efforts need to be made by HUD to ensure that the
department's (fair-market rents) realistically reflect prevailing
local market rents,'' the auditors said.
   Asked to comment, HUD issued a statement saying: ``While we have
every confidence in the way the fair market rents are computed we
welcome the suggestions from the inspector general's office and
want to work diligently with them to ensure that the system is
working properly.''
   The rents, which ultimately determine the amount of subsidies
HUD pays, are calculated through a formula that is supposed to
arrive at rents that are in line with similar, non-subsidized
apartments in the area, with the government rents perhaps slightly
higher to cover any rehabilitation costs.
   But the auditors said in some areas the fair-market rents set by
HUD are well above local market rents. For example, for all of
HUD's Region X _ Alaska, Washington, Oregon and Idaho _
overpayments were estimated between $12.9 million and $14.6 million
a year.
   The second audit, which dealt with the Section 8 program, found
that HUD did not advertise the availability of reserve funding at
the control of agency headquarters and that some of the subsidies
appeared to have been steered to specific housing agency and
developers.
   The auditors also said there was no documentation to support
seven subsidy awards, part of an overall problem of poor selection
guidelines and accountability.
   ``We believe that a commitment of federal funds of this
magnitude should require more than an informal process, i.e.,
documentation, criteria and rationale for the decisions,'' the
auditors wrote in the report, which was requested by the House
Banking Committee.
   The audit said $279 million was allocated from the reserve funds
for fiscal 1988 and 1989 and laid blame for the questionable
selection process on Thomas Demery, the former HUD assistant
secretary for housing.
   Demery, in comments included in the audit, said there had been
no formal system for awarding the money for more than a decade and
that he sought input from HUD's regional administrators before
making funding decisions.
   The new administration at HUD accepted the findings of that
audit without exception and has established written application
guidelines and ranking criteria for the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891007-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Panama     10-07 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Station Attacked; Reward Offered For Killing Noriega Opponents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed men burst into a radio station
that had broadcast a rebel communique against Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega. A Noriega supporter has offered $250,000 to kill six of
the general's enemies.
   A letter published Friday in the government newspaper Critica
said an unidentified businessman who made the offer presented the
letter to a columnist. It could not be confirmed.
   ``They (opponents) have allowed a price to be put on (Noriega's)
head, with dollars given to them by the United States,'' the letter
said. Therefore, ``we consider it justified to use our money to pay
those who execute traitors.''
   The six people threatened included former President Eric
Delvalle, who tried to fire Noriega last year and was dismissed,
and Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, a former top commander who was among
the first to accuse Noriega of drug trafficking.
   ``We have international contacts and there will be no difficulty
in carrying out these sworn duties,'' said the letter addressed to
columnist Balatazar Renan Aizprua, who also is chief spokesman for
the state power authority.
   It said the ``nationalist'' businessman deposited the money in a
Swiss bank account. It did not elaborate.
   Armed men in civilian clothes invaded a radio station Friday
that broadcast a rebel communique against Noriega during Tuesday's
botched coup. They destroyed broadcast equipment and forced
employees to leave.
   Threats to Noriega's enemies and the attack on the radio station
came after the general, who blames the coup on the United States,
said he would get tough with opponents. In a speech Thursday,
Noriega said radio stations that were ``bought off'' would be
``torn down.''
   In Washington, President Bush defended his handling of the coup
attempt, saying there was no opportunity to seize Noriega and that
use of U.S. force ``wasn't warranted under the existing
circumstances.''
   Bush said he would not rule out any option in a future coup
attempt, including military intervention.
   The six people threatened in the letter to Critica include
former President Eric Delvalle, who tried to fire Noriega last year
and was dismissed, and Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, a former top
commander who was among the first to accuse Noriega of drug
trafficking.
   Opposition leader Guillermo Endara continued a hunger strike
from the shelter of the papal nuncio's residence a day after he was
beaten and thrown out of his office by Noriega's soldiers.
   Endara's doctors examined him Friday and said he was in good
condition but could not talk to the press. He was in the 17th day
of a hunger strike to promote an opposition campaign against the
government.
   Endara launched his hunger strike as part of a campaign to
encourage Panamanians to delay tax payments and boycott government
lotteries and casinos.
   On television speech Thursday, Noriega ridiculed Endara's hunger
strike and said he had evidence the United States had planned to
install Endara as president.
   Endara was presidential candidate for an opposition coalition in
elections May 7. International observers said Endara's ticket beat
Noriega's candidate by a 3-1 margin, but Noriega had the election
annulled and appointed a provisional president.
   Noriega dominates Panama through his command of its police and
military, and the United States has been trying to oust him since
he was indicted on U.S. drug trafficking charges in February 1988.
   Noriega says the United States is trying to disavow treaties
that give his country control of the Panama Canal at the turn of
the century. He has withstood U.S. economic sanctions, elections
and two failed coups.
   In addition to Delvalle and Diaz Herrera, the businessmen's
letter threatened Juan B. Sosa, a former ambassador to the United
States, and Gabriel Lewis Galindo, Jose Isabel Blandon and Alberto
Garcia de Paredes _ all opponents of Noriega in exile.
</TEXT>
