<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Journalists     10-07 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Journalists,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramilitary Groups Harass Foreign Journalists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramilitary groups and members of
the Defense Forces have stepped up harassment of foreign
journalists since the failed rebellion of a military unit Tuesday.
   Soldiers wielding sticks and rubbers hoses Thursday night
attacked journalists gathered in front of the building where
oppositon leader Guillermo Endara was conducting a hunger strike.
Endara was beaten and forced to leave the building.
   Military strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega last year accused
foreign correspondents of being ``disinformers'' and blamed them
for the Panamanian government's bad image abroad.
   Since then, it has not been unusual for international
journalists to be detained for hours at a time, or to have film and
cameras confiscated without explanation.
   Government radio, newspapers and television accuse foreign
correspondents of being on the U.S. State Department's payroll.
   It is worse for the national press. Of the four main newspapers
in Panama City, three are government-owned. The director of the
only independently owned newspaper, La Estrella, is a friend of
Noriega's.
   The danger of running afoul of the regime was demonstrated by
the fate of Radio Exitosa, the only radio station to broadcast a
rebel communique during Tuesday's botched coup.
   On Thursday, Noriega said the United States had ``bought'' the
coup attempt and that radio stations in the pay of the U.S.
government should be destroyed. On Friday, the station was raided,
the employees driven off and its equipment destroyed.
   ``I try to keep a low profile,'' said a Panamanian reporter who
works for another station.
   Freedom of expression has suffered a ``big setback'' in Panama
this year, Manuel Jimenez, the president of the Inter-American
Press Association, said Friday in Monterrey, Mexico. He did not
elaborate, saying the issue would be discussed at next week's press
association convention in Monterrey.
   Thursday night's incidents began when men in civilian clothes
wielding guns and rubber hoses dispersed everyone in front of the
building where Endara was conducting his hunger strike.
   When journalists approached to ask questions the men pushed them
aside. Only one would talk, and all he would say was, ``Just get
out of here.''
   A typical attempt at intimidation involved beating the rubber
hoses on the sidewalk and yelling at journalists to scatter.
   When Endara's office was raided Thursday night, an Associated
Press photographer trying to take pictures was chased and beaten.
   ``Give us the camera,'' the soldiers shouted at photographer
John Hopper as they hit him with sticks. Hopper required seven
stitches to close a head cut, and the soldiers took his camera and
film.
   A cameraman for NBC News lost his video camera during Thursday
night's incident. A Japanese reporter said his car was taken.
   Some television journalists said they had to jump through
windows into private homes when they were chased by the soldiers.
   One U.S. correspondent said she and a photographer were forced
out of a taxi while covering the Endara incident.
   ``They forced us and the taxi driver out and they drove away
with the car,'' she said. Later two men dressed in fatigues rushed
her, grabbed her purse, spilled the contents on the ground and
demanded her car key.
   ``I convinced them I did not have a car, so they took $500,''
said the reporter.
</TEXT>
