<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-07 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Issues Largest-Ever Toxic Waste Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is fining
a California company $6.2 million for allegedly storing more toxic
wastes than it was authorized to handle.
   The civil penalty, the largest fine ever under federal toxic
waste disposal laws, was levied Friday against Casmalia Resources
of Casmalia, Calif., operator of a hazardous waste treatment,
storage and disposal facility.
   The EPA accused Casmalia Resources of ``accepting more hazardous
waste materials than its existing landfills were authorized to
handle.''
   The company also was charged with violating federal toxic waste
regulations because it improperly expanded its existing landfills
to accommodate additional wastes.
   EPA spokeswoman Robin Woods said the company must pay the fine
within 30 days or appeal.
   Before Friday's action, the largest penalty obtained by the EPA
for violation of the federal law governing toxic waste disposal was
$2.78 million last March against the Four County Landfill in
Rochester, Ind. That penalty came as a result of a federal judge's
ruling in a civil suit.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bush Makes History By Visiting Senate Floor</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush made a little history by
walking on to the Senate floor for a few seconds.
   Senate associate historian Don Ritchie said there's no record of
any sitting president making an informal visit to the floor,
although presidents have given formal addresses in the Senate
chamber.
   Normally, presidents speak in the larger House chamber to a
joint session of Congress.
   Bush decided to visit the floor after private meetings with
Senate Republicans and Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine.
He walked through the door to a round of applause from the handful
of senators on the floor and the mostly empty spectator gallery.
   The visit ended in less than a minute.
   Ritchie said Woodrow Wilson, Herbert Hoover, Richard Nixon and
Gerald Ford spoke in the Senate chamber during their presidencies.
Harry Truman and Ford visited the floor after their terms had ended.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bush to Host Margaret Thatcher at Camp David Next Month</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher will hold informal talks Nov. 24 at Camp David,
the presidential retreat in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, the
White House says.
   The meeting, a day after Thanksgiving, will be Bush's first
discussions with Mrs. Thatcher since the seven-nation economic
summit in Paris last July.
   Mrs. Thatcher also visited Camp David for talks with President
Reagan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Soviet Defense Minister Invites Cheney to Moscow</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has an
invitation to visit the Soviet Union.
   Soviet Defense Minister Dimitri Yazov ended his first U.S. visit
Friday by inviting Cheney to Moscow, praising American soldiers and
bragging about the impenetrability of his country's air defense
system.
   Yazov and appeared at a joint news conference where they pledged
a continuation of military exchanges, but made no substantive
announcements.
   Cheney, who said he would visit the Soviet Union at a
yet-to-be-decided time, said the military-to-military contacts
between the two superpower defense chiefs were ``very productive.''
   During the week, Yazov visited Camp Pendleton, a Marine training
base north of San Diego; Luke Air Force Base in Arizona; and Fort
Bragg, home of the Army's 82nd Airborne in Fayetteville, N.C.
   What impressed him most, Yazov said, were the soldiers _
``dedicated young men'' with a ``high level of training.''
