<HEAD>Police Chief During 1968 Riots Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John B. Layton, who served as police chief in
the nation's capital during the 1968 riots that followed the
assassination of civil rights leader Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.,
has died.
   Layton succumbed to a pulmonary embolism Thursday in Washington
Adventist Hospital. He was 77.
   He rose through the ranks of the Metropolitan Police Department
and was named chief in 1964. Layton retired less than five years
later after some of the most turbulent years in the city's history.
   His years at the helm coincided with a period of rapidly rising
crime, increased clashes between police and residents in many black
neighborhoods, and a series of court decisions that expanded the
rights of suspects in criminal cases.
