<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-LouisianaReferendum     10-07 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Referendum,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Amendments Include Gas Tax, Plan to Increase Black Judges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposals to encourage election of black
judges and boost the gasoline tax to finance highway construction
lead a list of state and local ballot questions before voters today.
   Secretary of State Fox McKeithen predicted that 33 to 35 percent
of the state's registered voters would go to the polls.
   There was little organized opposition to any of the 13 proposed
amendments to the state Constitution, and the transportation
measure drew the most statewide interest.
   The measure mirrored a proposal rejected by the voters April 29
when it was put forth by Gov. Buddy Roemer as part of a tax
revision plan.
   It would raise the gasoline tax by 4 cents per gallon to finance
$1.4 billion in transportation work, including widening highways
and expanding ports and airports. The measure also would require
that all 16 cents per gallon of the present motor fuel tax be used
for highways and public works projects.
   Roemer said the plan would boost efforts to attract new industry
to Louisiana and create thousands of construction jobs.
   ``I won't beat it to death, but it will be a powerful, positive
step forward for Louisiana and its taxpayers,'' the governor said.
   Two proposed amendments to the procedure for electing state
judges stem from federal lawsuits that contend that voting
districts are drawn to dilute black voting strength.
   There are no blacks on Louisiana's seven-member Supreme Court,
one black among the state's 52 appellate court judges and five
black district court judges out of 192.
   One amendment would add a judicial election district with a
majority of blacks in the New Orleans area and temporarily add a
justice to the state Supreme Court _ until the displaced incumbent
finishes out his term.
   Another amendment would create up to 35 black-majority
sub-districts for district and appellate courts.
   Among the other proposed constitutional amendments were one that
would make it easier for police to confiscate the property of
suspected drug dealers and another to set aside at least $5 million
a year in state mineral revenue to restore eroding wetlands.
   Several tax-related amendments were on the ballot, including
measures to raise the automobile license plate fee; to allow cities
and towns to raise property taxes; and to extend from five years to
10 years the current property tax assessment freeze for owners who
expand or improve buildings in certain districts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
