<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-APME-Gray     10-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-APME-Gray,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Gray Warns Editors Press Needs `Self-Control'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news industry far too eager to grab
the easy story has helped trivialize the nation's political life,
House Majority Whip William H. Gray told newspaper editors.
   ``I'll be very candid with you,'' said Gray. ``Eleven years ago
when I went to Congress, there were more press people who
understood what budget authority and outlays meant.
   ``Now you get people writing stories about budget policy who
don't even know what a budget outlay and a budget authority is.
Therefore, what they focus on is the superficial political
categorizations and charges.''
   Gray, a Pennsylvania Democrat, made his comments at a convention
of the Associated Press Managing Editors. He said an increasing
focus on ``the easy story'' has contributed to ``the trivialization
of American politics.''
   Gray last spring had his own brush with the press just before
his election to a House leadership post. News reports citing
unnamed sources said he was the target of an FBI investigation
about his office personnel policies.
   Those reports were later denied, but Gray said they were
symbolic of ``the more recent infatuation'' with the personal lives
of politicians.
   ``Am I advocating an end to public scrutiny? By no means,'' he
said. ``What I would recommend is greater self-control.
   ``Since there can be no all-encompassing definition of what
constitutes news, likewise there should be no predisposition that
all things involving public officials is news.''
   Gray's brush with controversy was among several involving ethics
in Congress, one of which led to the resignation of former Speaker
Jim Wright.
   Congress is likely to approve a new ethics code this fall, Gray
said.
   But there's a deeper problem, he added.
   ``The biggest problem I have as I look at the press in general
in Washington is a tendency to go for what I call the superficial,
the easy story where you can get into simple headlines, simple
bites,'' said Gray. ``I'm often terribly disappointed by that.
   ``It makes all of us in Washington look like a bunch of naughty
kids, calling each other names.''
   Gray said the focus on superficial events has a domino effect,
making politicians fit that style of coverage.
   ``Even more serious is the more recent infatuation with the
personal lives of public officials,'' he said. ``This preoccupation
is not a result of the trivialization of American politics, it is a
contributing factor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
