<FIRST>r a PM-APME-Officers     10-07 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-APME-Officers,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Associated Press Managing Editors Elect 1990 Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gene Foreman, managing editor of The
Philadelphia Inquirer, was elected president of the Associated
Press Managing Editors at the organization's annual meeting.
   Other new officers elected Friday are: Vice President Ralph
Langer, executive editor of The Dallas Morning News; Secretary Sue
Reisinger, managing editor of The Miami Herald's Broward County
edition, and Treasurer Alf Goodykoontz, executive editor of the
Richmond Times-Dispatch and The Richmond News Leader.
   The executive committee named Robert Ritter, executive editor of
The Denver Post, as chairman of the Continuing Studies Committee,
and Drake Mabry, executive editor of the Ames (Iowa) Daily Tribune,
as vice chairman.
   Elected to the APME Board of Directors for three-year terms were
incumbents Tom Marquardt of the The Capital in Annapolis, Md.;
David Zeeck of The Kansas City Star; W. Curtis Riddle of the
Journal &amp; Courier, in Lafayette, Ind., and Barbara Lombardo of The
Saratogian in Saratoga Springs, N.Y.
   Elected directors were Chris Peck of the Spokesman-Review and
Spokane (Wash.) Chronicle; Colleen Conant of The Commercial Appeal
in Memphis, Tenn.; Jerry Ceppos of the San Jose (Calif.) Mercury
News, and Caesar Andrews of The Reporter in Lansdale, Pa.
   The APME comprises news executives of the member papers of the
AP newsgathering cooperative.
</TEXT>
