<FIRST>u i PM-AirportStrike 1stLd-Writethru   10-07 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airport Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0417,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technicians Strike at Manila Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with work resuming after government
agrees to study demands, CORRECTS amount of increase demanded. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airport technicians demanding a pay
increase walked off the job early today but returned to work after
the government promised to study their requests, officials said.
   The seven-hour strike forced the cancellation of 70 domestic
flights nationwide and delays in international flights, said
Eduardo Carrascoso, manager of Ninoy Aquino International Airport.
   Necias Dayap, president of one of the two labor unions that went
on strike, said about 745 workers went on strike, including airport
communications and maintenance technicians. The strike left the
Manila airport without navigational aid and limited communication
facilities, Carrascoso said.
   Normal operations later resumed at the airport.
   Dayap said the workers, who make $178 a month, were demanding a
$18 pay increase to match the salaries of air traffic controllers.
</TEXT>
