<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     10-07 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Dissident Convicted; Radical Student Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge convicted the leader of South
Korea's largest dissident group today of making illegal contact
with communist North Korea and sentenced him to two years in prison.
   In a related development, prosecutors today indicted a radical
student charged with making an unauthorized trip to the North. If
convicted, she could be sentenced to death.
   Lee Bu-young, 46, co-chairman of the United National Democratic
Movement, South Korea's largest dissident organization, was
convicted of violating National Security Law and aiding an illegal
labor strike.
   Judge Lee Tae-woon of the Seoul District Criminal Court ruled
that the dissident contacted North Korea early this year to arrange
a meeting in defiance of a government ban.
   Under South Korean law, discussions on national unification may
not be conducted by unauthorized individuals.
   Lee Bu-young also was found guilty of violating the Labor Law
for allegedly aiding workers carrying out an illegal three-month
shipyard strike.
   Dissident sources said Lee was expected to appeal the conviction.
   The Seoul District Prosecutors' Office indicted Im Su-kyong, a
radical student who made an illegal trip to North Korea's capital
of Pyongyang to attend an international youth festival and discuss
unification with communist leaders.
   She was charged with traveling to the North on communist
instructions, giving the Pyongyang government information,
supporting communist causes and receiving money and goods while in
North Korea from June 30 to Aug. 15.
   It was not known when her case would come to trial.
   Ms. Im was arrested when she returned through the border truce
village of Panmunjom.
   Prosecutors said 23 people have been arrested in connection with
Ms. Im's case. The government has said it will prosecute those who
helped her or had prior knowledge of her illegal trip.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into the communist North and
capitalist South after World War II. The North invaded the South to
launch the three-year Korean War in 1950 and a peace treaty was
never signed, keeping the two sides technically at war.
   Although the two Koreas have held occasional talks aimed at
uniting the peninsula, they remain hostile enemies. The border
between the two nations is one of the most heavily fortified areas
in the world.
</TEXT>
