<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 0457EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-DalaiLama     10-07 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dalai Lama,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expresses Regret Over Nobel Peace Prize for Dalai Lama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today expressed ``utmost regret and
indignation'' over the awarding of the Nobel Peace Prize to the
Dalai Lama, saying the Tibetan spiritual leader is working to
undermine the national unity of the country.
   The Foreign Ministry reaction came two days after the Nobel
Committee announced the winner of the prize and a day after China's
official Xinhua News Agency condemned the choice.
   ``The decision taken by the Norwegian Nobel Committee to award
the Nobel Peace Prize to the Dalai Lama constitutes open support to
the Dalai Lama and the Tibetan separatists in their activities to
undermine the national unity and split China,'' the ministry said.
   ``It represents a gross interference in China's internal affairs
and seriously hurts the national feelings of the Chinese people.
Over this we express our utmost regret and indignation.''
   The ministry statement said the decision ``deviates from the
committee's purpose of awarding the prize to those working for and
contributing to `harmony and good will among peoples.'''
   The Nobel Committee, in giving the 54-year-old Buddhist monk the
peace prize, praised his dedication to non-violence and ``great
reverence for all things living.''
   China, however, blames the Dalai Lama and his followers for
instigating at least four major outbreaks of anti-Chinese,
pro-independence violence in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa in the
past two years.
   The Dalai Lama has lived in exile in northern India since
fleeing Lhasa in 1959 following a failed uprising against the
Chinese army.
   China says the remote mountain region of Tibet has been an
integral part of the nation since the 13th century.
   Many Tibetans demand independence, although the Dalai Lama last
year offered a compromise proposal under which Tibet would gain
self-autonomy but cede control of its defense and foreign affairs
to the Beijing government.
   China has rejected the proposal but says it is willing to meet
the Dalai Lama to discuss the Tibet question.
</TEXT>
