<FIRST>r i PM-EGermany-Color     10-07 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EGermany-Color,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Takes Center Stage At East German Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0460 to clarify garble in header. ^With PM-EGermany,
Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans turned their attention to
torchbearers and the charismatic Mikhail S. Gorbachev and away from
the thousands who fled westward shortly before the nation's 40th
anniversary festivities.
   The Soviet president was center stage Friday as he visited East
Berlin's war memorials and stood beside East German leader Erich
Honecker as tens of thousands of East German youth paraded by.
   He inspired cheers of ``Gorby! Gorby!'' from the crowd as he
broke ranks to chat and walk among them during the carefully staged
birthday celebrations Friday.
   But Gorbachev joined with East bloc leaders and other friends of
East Berlin, such as PLO chief Yasser Arafat and Nicarguan
President Daniel Ortega, for a lavish show of unity. The two-day
celebration ends today.
   There has been little mention of the exodus of disgruntled East
Germans that has captured world attention.
   Communist authorities worked hard to keep the focus on East
Germany's economic successes and off the turmoil. But hundreds more
East Germans fled Friday to freedom in the West, where at least
47,000 have found homes since early September.
   Police clashed with protesters in Dresden and Magdeburg, and
authorities barred Western tourists from East Berlin.
   Friday's anniversary events were capped by a parade in which
tens of thousands marched down the city's main boulevard carrying
flaming torches and chanting ``German Democratic Republic (East
Germany), our fatherland.''
   ``All of our energy and loyalty to the German Democratic
Republic,'' read one of the banners.
   Gorbachev and Honecker waved and smiled to the crowd. Blazing
beams of blue light cut into the night sky and laser images formed
doves of peace.
   Earlier, Gorbachev visited two war memorials and at one, walked
along columns etched with the words of Josef Stalin, a Soviet
predecessor whose course he has condemned.
   The Soviet leader was greeted along the motorcade route by
throngs of well-wishers. There were signs that East Germans hoped
Gorbachev's reform effort would penetrate the East Berlin
government, which has rejected radical change.
   ``He's trying to do a lot,'' said one young woman.
   The official message, however, presented the orthodox communist
line. Periodicals prepared for the event contrasted World War II
East Germany with the modern, rebuilt country today. Indeed, the
country is in the best shape economically of the Warsaw Pact allies.
   ``East Germany has achieved, through the courage and brilliance
and energy of its people, a life with more dignity and meaning,''
Honecker said in a hourlong speech to party members.
</TEXT>
