<FIRST>r a PM-Fonda'sDaughter     10-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fonda's Daughter,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Fonda's Daughter Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of actress Jane Fonda and filmmaker
Roger Vadim was charged with disorderly conduct and other
violations after police arrested her with a friend who was
allegedly carrying drugs.
   Vanessa Vadim, 21, was also charged Friday with obstructing
governmental administration and loitering for the purpose of
purchasing drugs, after narcotics officers saw her enter a building
known for narcotics trafficking, police said.
   She was being held today awaiting arraignment, said Stephen
Rivers, a spokesman for Ms. Fonda.
   He declined further comment on the case.
   Ms. Vadim was arrested with Thomas Feegal, 22, who was charged
with criminal possession of a controlled substance _ two glassine
envelopes believed to contain heroin and a hypodermic needle, said
a police spokesman, Sgt. Peter Sweeney.
   Police found no drugs on Ms. Vadim, the Daily News reported in
today's editions. The News said Ms. Vadim and Feegal, who was
described as her boyfriend, told police they bought the heroin
``for research purposes.''
   Narcotics officers saw Ms. Vadim and Feegal being led into a
known drug location at about 8 a.m., Sweeney said.
   As the two and a third person, Manuel Rivera, 30, emerged from
the building, the officers saw Feegal give a glassine envelope to
Rivera, he said.
   Eleven other arrests were made at the six-story building, which
has broken and boarded up windows and is frequented by junkies, the
News said.
   Feegal, a student at New York University, tried to flee as the
officers began the arrest, and when a police officer grabbed
Feegal, Ms. Vadim tried to pull him away from the officer, the
police spokesman said.
   Police said Rivera was also charged with drug possession.
   Ms. Vadim is the only daughter of Ms. Fonda, who also has a
15-year-old son, Troy, from her marriage to California state
Assemblyman Tom Hayden. Hayden and Ms. Fonda announced earlier this
year that they were separating.
   Ms. Vadim, a student at Brown University, was in New York to
attend the premiere of her mother's new movie, ``Old Gringo,''
which opened here Friday, according to a Fonda associate who
declined to be identified.
   Ms. Vadim and Ms. Fonda on Thursday attended a special screening
of the movie to benefit the Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Fund.
   Ms. Fonda had been scheduled to leave for Rome Friday but
postponed her plans because of her daughter's arrest, the
associated said.
</TEXT>
