<FIRST>r i PM-Haiti     10-07 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haiti,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Groups Denounce Abuses In Haiti</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Four international human rights
groups said there are persistent human rights violations in Haiti
and urged ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril to stick to his promises of
curbing abuses.
   The delegation from Americas Watch, the National Coalition for
Haitian Refugees, Caribbean Rights, and the International
Commission of Jurists issued a statement Friday after a weeklong
investigation in the impoverished Caribbean nation.
   ``We don't believe that violence and arbitrariness will cease
unless Avril's government proves by its acts that it is firmly
determined to put an end to them,'' the groups said in a statement.
   The delegation said it was worried about ``repeated acts of
repression'' against grass-roots organizations.
   It denounced the absence of legal action taken against thugs and
soldiers responsible for killings since dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled into exile in France in 1986.
   The delegation said those killers must be tried to discourage
``a repetition of these tragic moments in Haitian history.''
   The delegation said, however, the arrest of several soldiers for
various crimes, a new legal assistance program for the poor and
publication of an electoral timetable were all positive steps.
   Avril has pledged to turn over power to a civilian government.
The independent Electoral Council has set elections for autumn
1990, with the president to be sworn in on Feb. 7, 1991, exactly
five years after Duvalier left.
   ``Elections can only have meaning if all Haitian citizens are
free to speak, organize and assemble without fear of persecution,''
the communique said.
   The delegation said Avril assured them that his government
guaranteed the rights of speech and assembly.
   ``He declared that the violation of these rights was the result
of actions taken at the local level'' and that he had discharged
those responsible, the statement said.
</TEXT>
