<FIRST>r a PM-BarbaraBush     10-07 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Visits Teen Club, Praises Alcohol-Free Concept</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush paid a visit to a teen nightspot,
giving hundreds of students a break from school and a chance to
hear her praise for good, clean fun.
   Mrs. Bush made a brief Friday afternoon stop at the Basement, an
alcohol-free nightclub established last year by parents who wanted
to give teen-agers a safe place to go to on weekend nights.
   The club was closed this summer after six months because of poor
attendance, but it is scheduled to reopen at the end of the month
with live entertainment, movies and a game room.
   Students from several area schools were allowed to leave their
classes to accompany Mrs. Bush to the Basement.
   ``I can't wait to go back and tell George,'' she said from a
stage where rock 'n' roll bands usually play.
   ``I can't think of anything that meets the needs of our times
better than this,'' she said.
   Though Mrs. Bush got an enthusiastic reception during her
appearance, some of the students in the crowd said the main reason
they were at the Basement was because the event got them out of
school on a beautiful fall afternoon.
   Cason White, a 12th-grader at Pace Academy, said he rarely came
to the Basement, noting the regular $5 admission charge. ``It's
kind of expensive and out of the way,'' he said. He and his friends
said they'd rather go to parties.
   The atmosphere at the Basement, said classmate Jeffrey Cohen,
``seems so paranoid, it turns kids off.''
   Anne Landis, a spokeswoman for the club, said organizers are
hoping that changes made during the summer will make the Basement
more appealing to teen-agers. The club is striving to make the
adult supervision less conspicuous, she said.
   ``We don't want kids to think it's too straight-laced,'' Ms.
Landis said.
   Earlier Friday, Mrs. Bush told a convocation at the Morehouse
School of Medicine that the predominantly black college had made
her optimistic the nation's poor will receive better health care.
   Mrs. Bush is a former board member at the medical school,
founded by Health and Human Services Secretary Dr. Louis W.
Sullivan. Its mission is to provide doctors for poor, mainly
inner-city areas.
   She noted that the school's student body is growing rapidly. It
has a 95 percent passing rate on national board tests and has never
experienced an operating budget deficit.
   ``I'm not naive enough to think the graduates of Morehouse will
solve all the health problems ... but I'm optimistic,'' Mrs. Bush
said.
</TEXT>
