<FIRST>r a PM-VanGogh-Irises 1stLd-Writethru a0479 10-07 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Van Gogh-Irises, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Put Up Half of $54 million to Buy `Irises'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT spelling of Christie's sted
Christies's; adds background on painting in last graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's loaned Australian businessman Alan
Bond half of the record $53.9 million he paid for Vincent van
Gogh's ``Irises'' in 1987, a spokeswoman for the famed auction
house said.
   Bond has repaid ``significantly more than half'' of the
approximately $27 million he borrowed, Sotheby's spokeswoman Diana
Levitt said Friday.
   She declined to discuss the terms of the loan but said the
auction house has offered loans to its clients for at least 10
years.
   ``There's nothing new here,'' she said. ``Our loan service is
something we are delighted to provide to our clients. We do it
carefully and conservatively.''
   Many in the art world had through the market for fine art would
suffer after the Oct. 19, 1987, crash of the stock market, but
those concerns were laid aside when Bond bought ``Irises'' the next
month at a price that remains unsurpassed for a piece of art.
   Levitt denied assertions by some in the art industry that the
loan for ``Irises'' fueled the skyrocketing prices in the art world.
   ``The art market is very strong,'' Levitt said.
   She said that of the top nine artworks auctioned at huge prices,
only ``Irises'' was financed. Rival auction house Christie's has
said it declines to finance purchases.
   Levitt noted that three potential buyers were vying for
``Irises'' when the bidding reached the $40 million level. The
painting was made in 1889 while van Gogh was living in a mental
asylum in the south of France. He died the following year.
</TEXT>
