<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo     10-07 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barrier Island Bridge Repair Like Christmas in October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reopening of the storm-racked Sawyer
Bridge was like Christmas in October, says the mayor of an island
that has been cut off from traffic since it was savaged by
Hurricane Hugo.
   The swing bridge was partly reopened Friday, easing life for
residents who had been forced to make limited boat trips to the
Isle of Palms and Sullivans Island to survey the storm damage and
salvage their possessions.
   ``I kind of felt like a kid waiting for Christmas,'' said
Sullivans Island Mayor C. Melvin Anderegg. ``I felt like it was
never going to come.''
   In other developments, President Bush boosted the federal
government's pledged contribution to recovery efforts, and South
Carolina raised its estimate of the storm's damage toll to $4
billion to $5 billion.
   Hugo hit the at Charleston coast on Sept. 21 with 135 mph winds,
squashing scores of buildings and leaving thousands without
electricity and other necessities. The storm killed 29 people on
the U.S. mainland and 33 in the Caribbean.
   Hugo twisted a span of the Ben Sawyer Bridge awry and left one
end dangling into the Intracoastal Waterway. Raised and reconnected
at a cost of $1 million, the only road link to the two barrier
islands was opened Friday to one lane of traffic, with the
direction switching every two hours during daylight.
   The first motorist to cross was Carmen Bunch, mayor of Isle of
Palms, who welcomed the respite from awkward boat trips to her home.
   ``It was wonderful not to have to climb over rocks, not to have
to climb over docks and then get into a car,'' Ms. Bunch said.
   Added Karen Brown of Sullivans Island: ``It was nice not to be
wet coming home. ... We just wanted to get home and check on the
cats.''
   Traffic was limited to residents of the islands or people with
business there, said Highway Patrol Capt. H.G. Holloman.
   Engineers were still inspecting the bridge, and hadn't
determined when it could be opened to allow boats to pass.
   Also Friday, the White House announced the federal government
would shoulder a larger share of the relief burden than is normal
under rules of the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   Washington will pay 75 percent of all eligible costs up to $34
million, and above that amount it will pay all costs, according to
the White House.
   FEMA normally pays 75 percent of repairs to roads, bridges,
publicly held utilities, parks and certain non-profit facilities,
with state state and local governments picking up the rest.
   The change will save state and local governments in South
Carolina at least $20 million, said Gov. Carroll Campbell.
   Damage in South Carolina had been conservatively estimated at $3
billion, but on Thursday, Campbell announced that experts had
revised that upward to $4 billion to $5 billion. The new estimate
was based on discussions with county officials, state department
chiefs and emergency management officials, said Campbell's
spokesman, Tucker Eskew.
</TEXT>
