<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Soviet,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Employee Seeks to Defect to Soviet Union, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government employee
apparently seeking to defect to the Soviet Union has traveled to
London and was staying with Soviet officials, a pro-government
newspaper reported today.
   Susan Dobson, who worked for the Bureau for Information, left
her job in neighboring Namibia on Sept. 24 and met with officials
at the Soviet observer mission in the territory before going to
London, according to The Citizen.
   The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said Ms. Dobson was
``with the Russians in London.'' The Citizen also said that the
26-year-old woman probably had access to ``sensitive information.''
   Meanwhile, the woman's father, A.E. Millson, confirmed that his
daughter was in London but denied that she was trying to defect,
according to The Saturday Star of Johannesburg.
   ``We are convinced she suffered a mental breakdown,'' Millson
was quoted as saying by The Star.
   The Bureau of Information said, ``Ms. Dobson has not yet given
any reason for her behaviour to the ... authorities.''
   ``She was very tense and emotionally upset during Saturday
afternoon (Sept. 23) preceding her departure,'' the bureau said in
a statement Friday.
   The bureau said Mrs. Dobson, who helped prepare press releases,
had been fired.
   The independent South African Press Association quoted
unidentified sources as saying that Ms. Dobson traveled with a
foreign television crew to northern Namibia Sept. 20, then shunned
colleagues when she returned three days later to Windhoek, the
territorial capital.
   She spent the night at a U.N. military base, and the following
day was taken to the Soviet mission, the press association said.
   Afterward, she called her husband in South Africa. They met in
Botswana and flew to Britain, the report added.
   Officials of the U.N. monitoring force in Namibia could not
immediately be reached for comment. South Africa, which has ruled
Namibia for 74 years, has agreed to grant the territory
independence under a U.N.-monitored process including elections
next month for a national assembly.
</TEXT>
