<SECOND>PM-Arias Speech, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Warns Against U.S. Military Action in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT spelling of Antonio. SUBS 5th graf, `Arias
chided..', to add that Arias won Nobel Peace Prize in 1987.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias
Sanchez warned against U.S. military action against Panamanian
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, and said all of Central America
desperately needs economic growth.
   ``It is true that he is a despot,'' Arias said Friday. ``It is
true that he is a shame to the whole of Latin America. But I simply
could not be in favor of military action. I think the Panamanians
will take care of him. I think we need to be a little bit patient.''
   Arias, on a visit to attract investment by electronics companies
in Costa Rica, urged economic sanctions against Panama. He said
Gen. Noriega, Panama's de facto military leader, already was
diplomatically isolated.
   ``The minute you send in your Marines, Noriega will have more
solidarity from the rest of the Latin American countries,'' Arias
said. ``It is the wrong thing to do.''
   Arias, the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize winner for his efforts to
bring peace to Central America, chided members of Congress who
criticized President Bush for not using the full strength of the
12,000-man U.S. military force in Panama to help rebellious
officers in the failed coup attempt on Tuesday.
   ``The problem is there are some people here in Washington who
never read past history,'' Arias said.
   Arias met with leaders of many high-technology companies at a
business luncheon and toured an Apple Computer Co. plant before
speaking at a dinner held by the World Affairs Council of Northern
California and the World Forum of Silicon Valley.
   Arias said most countries in Latin America that have been trying
to develop democracy are struggling with their economies and need
U.S. assistance.
   ``We should not be trapped into waiting for political
development before economic change takes place,'' Arias said.
``Democracy is certainly indispensable for peace, but so are
economic growth and justice.''
   Unless the region's debt problems are resolved, he said, ``we
are inviting dictators to come back.''
