<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 3rdLd-Writethru   10-07 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0491,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells East Germans To Solve Their Own Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more details on talks and
barriers set up at Checkpoint Charlier. Pickup 7th graf, `Many have...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev today met
with East German leader Erich Honecker, a day after encouraging the
hard-line government in East Berlin to work with ``all forces in
society.''
   Gorbachev was in East Berlin during the country's 40th
anniversary celebrations, which have been overshadowed by the
exodus of nearly 50,000 refugees who fled to the West in search of
greater freedom and opportunity.
   In a brief dispatch, the state-run news agency ADN said the two
leaders had started their meeting but did not describe the
substance of the talks.
   In a formal address the night before, Gorbachev said: ``There is
no doubt that the Socialist Unity Party (East German Communist
Party) has the intellectual potential, rich experience and
political authority to cooperate with all forces in society to
answer the questions placed on today's agenda.''
   The mass-circulation Bild newspaper in West Germany said Friday
that Gorbachev planned to encourage Honecker to make several
changes, including easing travel restrictions for East Germans and
allowing greater freedom of expression. Honecker has been unwilling
to implement the economic and political reforms now under way in
the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary.
   For the third straight day, East Germany today barred Western
tourists from entering Communist East Berlin, also erecting three
barriers at the crossing called Checkpoint Charlie by the Western
allies.
   The 6-foot-tall barriers were set up overnight on the East
German side of the checkpoint. They apparently are designed to stop
protests similar to those Aug. 13, the anniversary of the start of
construction of the Berlin Wall, when demonstrators tried to lie
down on the dividing line between the two sectors and hurled
objects at East German border police.
   ``East Germany apparently fears that regime-critics coming from
West Germany could disturb the 40th anniversary celebrations,''
said West Germany's ARD television.
   The Soviet leader, who was to return home later today, was
hailed by youths who shouted ``Gorby! Gorby!'' as he stood beside
Honecker during a three-hour Communist youth parade.
   Many have said democratic change might stem the westward flow of
East German youth and avoid divisions among the East bloc nations.
   East Germany's leaders wanted the anniversary to portray their
country as a socialist success.
   ``All of our energy and loyalty to the German Democratic
Republic,'' read one of the parade banners. But the exodus of
thousands of its citizens to the West from embassies in
Czechoslovakia and Poland, and violent clashes between East Germans
and police have focused world attention on the country's turmoil.
   To squelch any possible protests during the anniversary, the
Communist leadership stepped up security nationwide.
   Church sources today said police arrested eight members of the
country's leading opposition group, New Forum.
   Unconfirmed reports said the government was mounting barbed wire
fences on the border with neighboring Poland and Czechoslovakia,
which East German refugees used as stepping stones to the West.
   West Germany's ZDF television said a caller from East Germany
said Friday barbed wire was being strung along the frontier with
Czechoslovakia. The newspaper Die Welt said East German authorities
were preparing to build fences along the Polish border.
   As anniversary festivities were about to begin in East Germany
Friday, a train carrying more than 600 disgruntled citizens rolled
into West Germany from Warsaw. The same number crossed into Austria
from Hungary early today.
   Thousands more traveled to the West earlier in the week aboard
other trains after East Germany, in what seemed an attempt to
polish its image, set free refuge-seekers camping at West German
embassies in Prague and Warsaw.
   In a formal address late Friday before the East German
leadership, Gorbachev said the East German Communist Party can
manage the country's own affairs.
   ``We have heard demands such as the U.S.S.R. should take down
the Berlin Wall and then people could believe in its (the Soviets')
peaceful aims,'' said Gorbachev. ``Our Western partners should
understand that questions regarding the GDR (East Germany) are not
solved in Moscow but in Berlin.''
   But without being specific, Gorbachev also called on the
authoritarian leadership to reach out to all elements in society.
   ``There is no doubt that (East Germany's Communist Party) has
the intellectual potential, rich experience and political authority
to cooperate with all forces in society to answer the questions
placed on today's agenda,'' he said.
   The Soviet leader defended Moscow's reforms.
   In his own address, Honecker, the 77-year-old East German leader
who has run the country for more than 18 years, reaffirmed the
country's hard line and condemned what he said were international
efforts aimed at the ``destabilization of socialism.''
</TEXT>
