<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   10-07 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0496,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Moscow to Defend Yeltsin, Other Deputies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD background on Yeltsin, other parliamentarians,
protest occurs while Gorbachev in East Germany. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Soviets marched to the walls of the
Kremlin today to show support for Boris N. Yeltsin and two other
parliamentarians they claim are threatened by hard-line Communist
Party bureaucrats.
   The protest, held on Constitution Day, a Soviet holiday, was
also staged to demand that the civil and human rights enshrined in
the 1977 Soviet Constitution be observed.
   In a near-freezing drizzle, members and sympathizers of the
grassroots pro-democracy Russian People's Front linked hands at 11
a.m. to form a human chain that stretched for miles along Gorky
Street, the main artery leading from the Kremlin to Moscow's
northwestern suburbs.
   Demonstrators carried placards defending Yeltsin, Moscow's
outspoken representative in the Soviet Congress, and two state
prosecutors in the Congress, Telman Gdlyan and Nikolai Ivanov, who
have alleged corruption at the party's highest levels involving
Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev.
   Yeltsin, the former Communist Party boss in Moscow, came under
attack late last month in the party daily Pravda for allegedly
going on a drinking and buying spree while visiting the United
States.
   Pravda later apologized to Yeltsin, saying those charges, made
in an Italian newspaper article that Pravda reprinted, could not be
substantiated. But to Soviets, the affair was more proof that the
party apparatus was out to get the 58-year-old Communist maverick
who has opposed privileges received by the party elite and called
for a better life for the average Soviet.
   In the case of Gdlyan and Ivanov, the party's policy-making
Central Committee has ordered the Moscow party organization to take
action against them for making the charges against Ligachev, which
the Soviet prosecutor-general's office said have no basis.
   ``Yeltsin, Gdlyan and Ivanov are our conscience!'' said one
hand-lettered poster carried by a Gorky Street protester.
   In leaflets distributed throughout the Soviet capital, the
People's Front had called for Muscovites to line Gorky Street from
central Moscow to the suburban city of Zelenograd, which Gdlyan
represents in the Congress, but organizers said bad weather kept
participation down.
   Nevertheless, knots of protesters were seen as far away as
Sheremetyevo Airport, Moscow's international airport 20 miles from
the Kremlin.
   After making the human chain, 3,000 demonstrators marched to a
paved square on Marx Prospekt between the Kremlin's high, red-brick
walls and the former quarters of Moscow State University, which now
house its journalism school.
   Huddled under umbrellas, they listened to People's Front leaders
make speeches through bullhorns, then marched back up Gorky Street
to Pushkin Square to take part in another demonstration calling for
an end to government restrictions on emigration.
   The protests occurred while President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was
in East Germany to attend ceremonies marking the country's 40th
anniversary. Yeltsin first got in trouble with Gorbachev for
claiming the president's program of economic and political reforms
was being implemented too slowly.
</TEXT>
