<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru a0483 10-07 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Closes Sidon Operations After Kidnapping of Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 13th pvs, `Amer said...' with 1 graf to restore first reference
to guerrilla spokesman. Pickup 14th pvs, `Moein Shabaita...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Committee of the Red
Cross suspended operations in this southern port city today after
two Swiss relief workers were kidnapped, a Red Cross official said.
   ``Our operations have been suspended in Sidon pending the
release of our two abducted comrades,'' said Mohammed Bizri, the
Lebanese representive of the Red Cross in Sidon.
   The announcement came a day after masked gunmen grabbed Emanuel
Cristen, 32, and Elio Elliquez, 23, shoved them into a car trunk
and drove toward a suburban Palestinian refugee camp. The two were
orthopedic technicians who helped fit artificial limbs for victims
of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   The pair were kidnapped outside a Red Cross center near the
refugee camp of Ein el-Hilweh on Sidon's southeastern outskirts.
   Bizri said the center was closed indefinitely and ``all Swiss
Red Cross'' officials based in Sidon were withdrawn to Beirut.
   It was the second time within a year that the Red Cross withdrew
from some operations in Lebanon. It withdrew all 31 Swiss nationals
from the country following the November 1988 kidnapping of Swiss
relief worker Peter Winkler. Winkler was freed a month later, and
Swiss workers returned only after receiving assurances from all
sides in Lebanon that there would be no more attacks on
humanitarian organizations.
   ``Contacts are under way on all levels to help win release of
the two Swiss officials but we still have no word on their
whereabouts or who is holding them,'' Bizri said.
   No group claimed reponsibility for the abduction, the latest in
a series targeting humanitarian workers in south Lebanon. Previous
kidnappings were blamed on a radical guerrilla faction headed by
Palestinian Abu Nidal.
   Abu Nidal is the nom de guerre of Sabri al-Banna, who broke from
Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction in 1973 and set up a rival
group called Fatah-Revolutionary Council.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization, which governs Ein
el-Hilweh, and a Sidon-based Sunni Moslem militia have vowed to
track down the kidnappers.
   PLO spokesman Zeid Wehbeh had pledged to ``spare no effort'' to
help rescue the men.
   A Fatah guerrilla who identified himself only as Amer said all
exits of Ein el-Hilweh were under constant surveillance to prevent
the kidnappers from trying to smuggle out the Swiss captives.
   Moein Shabaita, a spokesman for Fatah faction, the PLO's main
group, linked the kidnappings to a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, Mohammed
Hariri, jailed for life in Switzerland in February for hijacking an
Air Afrique jetliner. A French passenger was killed in the July 24,
1987 hijacking.
   Shabaita said Christen and Erriquez were kidnapped, ``apparently
for the purpose of trying to win Hariri's release.''
   Eighteen Westerners, including eight Americans, are missing in
Lebanon. Most are believed captives of Shiite Moslems loyal to Iran.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   At least 10 relief workers _ British, West Germans,
Scandinavians, Belgians and Swiss _ have been abducted in southern
Lebanon in the past two years. All but two have been freed.
   In Beirut, acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss today condemned the
latest abduction as ``a cowardly act harmful to our country and
society.''
   Hoss said in a statement that he had ordered police forces in
south Lebanon to ``make every possible effort'' to help win release
of the captives.
</TEXT>
