<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0461 10-07 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0461,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Careless Smoking Cause of Nursing Home Blaze</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4-5th grafs, `The real...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
today's condition report, which still lists seven people in critical condition,
add detail on ages of victims. Picks up 6th graf, `The fire...'. DELETES
last graf pvs, redundant material.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursing home fire that killed nine
patients and injured nearly 100 was caused by one of its victims _
a 78-year-old smoker who accidentally tossed a match on his bed
when he missed a trash can.
   Authorities said Friday that despite the high death toll, they
considered it lucky more people weren't killed in the fire that
broke out late Thursday in the four-story Hillhaven Rehabilitation
and Convalescent Center.
   Thick, black smoke from burning foam rubber mattresses filled
the hallways, hampering evacuation already made difficult by the
frail condition of many of the patients, said Fire Chief Thomas E.
Gardner.
   ``The real problem was the smoke and the fragileness of the
elderly residents' lungs,'' Gardner said. The dead were eight women
and one man, ranging in age from 65 to 97.
   Seven of the injured were listed in critical condition this
morning at Sentara Norfolk General Hospital. Ninety-eight residents
were treated after the fire for smoke inhalation, said Don Haupt,
administrator of the city's Paramedical Rescue Service.
   The fire broke out in the second-floor room of Major Leary, 78,
said Capt. Herbert Redfield, chief of Fire Investigations. Smoking
is prohibited in rooms at the home, but Leary, who was recuperating
from hip problems, had been caught with cigarettes the night of the
blaze, said Jeffrey M. McKain, Hillhaven Corp. vice president.
Smoking is allowed in lounges and public areas.
   ``He was asked last night if he had cigarettes and he said no,''
McKain said Friday. ``But it's easy for a determined patient to get
around rules.''
   A nurse checked Room 226 about 10 p.m. and found Leary sitting
in a chair near the foot of his bed and his roommate asleep,
Redfield said.
   As investigators reconstruct the scene, Leary lit a cigarette
and tossed the match toward a metal trash can about three inches
from the foot of the bed, Redfield said. The match landed on the
bed, setting the covers and mattress ablaze.
   Leary was among those who died in the fire.
   Gardner, the fire chief, said there probably would have been
fewer deaths if there had been fire sprinklers at the nursing home.
But he said the home met all building codes when it was built in
1969 and had passed two state inspections this year.
   Gardner said that further deaths were prevented by several
factors: strong fire walls and fire resistant doors, quick response
by more than 100 Norfolk firefighters and paramedics, the use of a
giant pressurized ventilation system that pumped fresh air through
the building _ and plain luck.
   ``We were just lucky,'' Gardner said. ``Lucky more didn't die.''
</TEXT>
