<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Philippines-Typhoon     10-07 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Philippines-Typhoon,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Injures Four, Damages Homes, Crops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Angela battered the
mountainous northern Philippines Saturday and forced more than
8,500 people to flee their homes for evacuation centers, officials
said.
   Initial reports reaching relief agencies in Manila said the
storm injured four people, damaged or destroyed 34 houses in three
northern provinces, uprooted about $75,000 worth of crops and
caused extensive flooding.
   The storm then headed out of the country toward mainland China.
   The Philippine military Office of Civil Defense said about 2,003
families, or 8,846 people, were forced to leave their homes and
stay in evacuation centers in Ilocos Norte province on the northern
tip of the main Luzon island.
   A spokesman for the office said most of its provincial chapters
failed to give reports because the typhoon toppled many electrical
and telephone posts.
   Detailed damage and casualty reports from remote areas often
take days or weeks to reach the capital due to poor communications.
