<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 1248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SierraLeone     10-07 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sierra Leone,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sierre Leone Hangs Six Convicted of Treason</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former vice president, a former
senior police official and four soldiers were hanged Saturday for
plotting to kill President Joseph Momoh and overthrow his
government, official sources said.
   Government-controlled radio said Momoh commuted to life
imprisonment the death sentences of six other men convicted in the
attempted coup.
   The men were among 18 people convicted in the failed coup on
March 23, 1987, in which a police officer was killed. The national
appeals court upheld the death sentences last month.
   Those hanged at dawn Saturday included former Vice President
Francis Minah and Mohammed Gabriel Tennyson Kaikai, former
assistant police superintendent, according to the government
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Sierra Leone is a former British colony in western Africa that
became an independent member of the Commonwealth in 1961 and a
republic in 1971.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
