<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-US Base,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Rally Outside U.S. Base in Okinawa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police scuffled with 500 protesters staging a
sit-in outside a U.S. military base in Okinawa on Saturday to
protest a plan to build an anti-guerrilla training center there,
police said.
   Several people were injured, including a 26-year-old man who was
taken to a hospital with a possible broken rib, police said.
   About 35,000 American troops are stationed on Okinawa in
southern Japan.
   An officer at the Ishikawa police station said the brief scuffle
occurred outside U.S.-run Camp Hansen when police were called to
remove the protesters.
   Prior to that, U.S. military authorities canceled plans to take
15 truckloads of construction materials into the camp, said the
officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The protesters chanted slogans describing the proposed
anti-guerrilla training center as an expansion of U.S. military
facilities on Okinawa.
   U.S. military authorities were not available for comment.
