<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 1421EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-07 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court or no, it's one American
flag no one will be able to set afire _ a 12-foot-tall U.S. flag
made out of a spare, steel beam.
   ``The point of this is to show in a symbolic way that there's
something you can't destroy, and that's the American flag,'' said
Frank Gallo, an art professor at the University of Illinois. He
teamed up with a friend, metal worker Aaron Kurland, to create the
sculpture unveiled Friday along a city street.
   The two call the sculpture ``The Flag That Will Not Burn.'' They
were inspired by the uproar over flag desecration, but Gallo also
sensed a challenge.
   ``It seemed to be almost the antithesis of an I-beam,'' Gallo
said. ``The contrast is so interesting. What a challenge it would
be to see if we can create a sense of fluid movement inside of
something that absolutely couldn't be conceived of as moving.''
   The sculpture is designed to catch sunlight at various times of
the day, and there are plans to light it up at night.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEED, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco Symphony had to slim down
to 80 musicians to fit on stage during a performance in the small,
windswept town of Weed.
   The symphony, usually 106 pieces, was coaxed to Weed in far
northern California by pleas from some residents for big-city
culture.
   The 625-seat auditorium where the symphony performed Thursday
night was the smallest hall ever played by the orchestra.
   ``The orchestra treats this with the same seriousness as playing
New York,'' said Peter Pastreich, the symphony's executive director.
   Some residents of Weed, a town of 3,000 nearly 300 miles north
of San Francisco, had to sit on folding chairs in the aisles during
the concert.
   ``It's something we'll never see again in our lifetime,'' said
Siskiyou County Supervisor Ivan Young.
</TEXT>
