<FIRST>r a AM-HangnailHandicap     10-07 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hangnail Handicap,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Sued For Claims of Using Handicapped Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state sued a company that sells
light bulbs over the telephone, charging it claims all its
employees are handicapped when they may have nothing more disabling
than hangnails or hay fever.
   The lawsuit filed Friday in Jackson County court said workers
for Local Handicapped Workers Inc. have called thousands of people
in Missouri since last April, claiming that ``all the employees
here are handicapped.'' Then the solicitors asked the customers to
buy light bulbs for up to $5.41 each.
   Investigators from state Attorney General William L. Webster's
office say that when they posed as job applicants at the business,
supervisors told them they could earn up to $600 a week and that
``handicaps'' could include pregnancy, hangnails, allergies or the
need for eyeglasses.
   ``I seriously doubt anyone who purchased light bulbs from the
company would consider wearing glasses a handicap,'' Webster said.
``We contend the company misled consumers by telling them a group
of handicapped people were selling light bulbs for a living.''
   When one investigator could not identify a handicap, the manager
``told her to go home and think of a handicap and call back'' and
she would be hired, according to the lawsuit.
   The lawsuit seeks $1,000 for each violation of state consumer
fraud laws, and refunds for people who bought bulbs from the
company.
   An attorney for the company, Dan Allmayer, said the company
denies the charges. Meanwhile, a court order bars it from using the
word handicapped in its sales pitches.
</TEXT>
