<FIRST>r w AM-CondomPamphlet     10-07 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Condom Pamphlet,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government AIDS Booklet Mired in Crossfire at HHS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publication of an AIDS-education pamphlet on
the use of condoms has run into another delay at the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   The brochure has been circulating at the department for two
years and recently was sent back for review by Kay James, assistant
secretary for public affairs, who said she wanted it to be more
specific about condom failures.
   James, a former director of public affairs for the National
Right to Life Committee, also said in an interview Saturday that
she wanted more information about the audience the brochure was
intended to reach.
   ``That wasn't made clear to me _ whether it would be widely
distributed or given just to high school students,'' she said.
``You would do a different brochure for different audiences.''
   James acknowledged that she sent the brochure back to the Public
Health Service for further review, but denied her action was
ideologically driven.
   ``Peoples lives are at stake,'' she said. ``When people are
making decisions about their sexual behavior ... they need to have
accurate information and that's my only concern.''
   However, sources within the Public Health Service who spoke on
the condition of anonymity, said some people have expressed concern
because they believe James is personally opposed to using public
money to promote condom use.
   The Washington Post, in Saturday editions, quoted a senior
federal health official as saying: ``We have a major battle on our
hands, and we are fighting with at least one arm tied behind our
back. How can we explain that in the 10th year of an epidemic that
has killed so many of our young people, we are not able to help
them use the only method we know can help.''
   Former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who was often at odds
with the Reagan administration over his advocacy of condom use,
also said the brochure is needed.
   ``In view of the large number of letters the Public Health
Service has received about concerns on how to use a condom, it
seems clear that such a brochure is long overdue,'' Koop told the
Post.
   James Allen, director of the National AIDS Program Office, said
Saturday that a brochure on condom use is needed but acknowledged
that such a document raises concern for some.
   ``As a federal government that is paying for it with tax dollars
we are subject to a lot of criticism, but that doesn't mean we shy
away,'' he said. ``It means we try to take different sensitivities
into view.''
   The pamphlet is being reviewed by Jeff Nesbit, head of public
affairs for the Food and Drug Administration, who said it had been
sent to James office by his predecessor and that he had not yet
looked through it.
   ``I consider this part of the normal review process,'' he said.
``It is not all that unusual.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
