<FIRST>r a AM-ObsceneArtShow     10-07 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obscene Art Show,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallery Owner Opens `Taboo' Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obscene Art</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDITH A. RUSSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gallery owner has put together an art exhibit
that offers something to offend just about everyone, including
works by two artists who outraged Sen. Jesse Helms and led to the
bill just passed in Congress.
   Greg Kucera assembled the 20-artist show, called ``Taboo,'' with
his own money, saying ``people have a right to see these works of
art.''
   ``We live in a world where diversity of opinion gives this
culture its richness,'' Kucera said. Without the right to examine
controversial and sometimes disturbing works of art, ``we would be
fascists.''
   Many if not most of the works would presumeably not be eligible
to receive public funds from the National Endowment for the Arts
and the National Endowment for the Humanities under a bill approved
by the Senate on Saturday after passing the House of
Representatives earlier in the week. The bill gives officials the
power to deny grant money to artworks they deem obscene.
   Kucera's show includes works by two artists who angered some
lawmakers, most notably Helms, the North Carolina Republican who
led the effort to prohibit federal aid for art he considers
offensive.
   Helms noted the National Endowment for the Arts had spent
$45,000 to back an exhibit by Andres Serrano, which featured a
photograph titled ``Piss Christ'' of a crucifix in what is
allegedly urine, and by the late Robert Mapplethorpe, whose
photographs depict homosexual acts and children in explicit poses.
   Helms' proposal sought to prohibit federal aid for ``obscene''
or indecent art, and for works offensive to a religion, ethnic or
age group, race, or the disabled.
   A compromise version, approved by the House and now before the
Senate, would bar the endowments from issuing grants for
exhibitions considered ``obscene,'' including works depicting
sadomasochism, homoeroticism, sexual exploitation of children or
people involved in sex acts. Officials would also have to find the
work lacks ``serious literary, artistic, political or scientific
value.''
   Serrano's ``Piss Christ'' and some works by Mapplethorpe are
included in Kucera's show, which opened Thursday and runs through
Oct. 29.
   Kucera said about 1,000 people, five times the normal number,
showed up opening night and that the catalog is selling briskly.
   Kucera boarded up the plate glass windows in his small
storefront gallery before the opening and hired a private security
guard. But by late Friday only one protester had appeared.
   The artists in the exhibit all have found themselves the subject
of controversy at one time or another, Kucera says.
   It includes a crucified Mickey Mouse titled ``Homage to Jim
Bakker'' by a Winston-Salem, N.C., artist who goes by the name
Richard C. Other religious themes are the late Howard Kottler's
``Bar Mitzvah Boy,'' a plate featuring a portrait of a pope and
Athens, Ga., artist Bill Paul's bound and nailed-shut bible.
   Photographs of sometimes naked, bloodied or bruised children in
the exhibit are Lexington, Va., artist Sally Mann's own children,
and the bruises and bloody noses were the result of the usual
childhood horseplay, Kucera said.
</TEXT>
