<FIRST>r w AM-ThornburghTravels 1stLd-Writethru a0563 10-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh Travels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0563,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Defends Private Use of Government Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, Runkel said, to DELETE reference to Japan;
picks up 11th graf, But a</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is defending Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh's use of government aircraft for private
travel, including a trip to a convention in Hawaii aboard a Boeing
727 in which he and five assistants were the only passengers.
   David Runkel, a spokesman for Thornburgh, said the Federal
Bureau of Investigation ``has determined that for his personal
security and the security of his communications that he should
travel by government airplane.''
   The FBI is a branch of the Justice Department, which Thornburgh
heads.
   Runkel said Thornburgh was surprised, however, to learn that the
only government aircraft for the Hawaii trip was a 727, a large,
commercial-sized jet used by the U.S. Marshals Service to fly
prisoners around the country.
   ``He thought that it was bizarre when he got inside the plane,
but the 727 was the only plane available that could get him
there,'' Runkel said.
   The flight from San Francisco to Honolulu cost the government
$38,000, according to a report Saturday in The New York Times. The
paper said it had examined records showing that Thornburgh's 48
trips in the last year cost taxpayers $191,000.
   The General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress,
is looking into the trips, the paper reported.
   More than a year ago, Thornburgh restricted government-paid
travel by Justice Department employees to trips directly related to
the job. Conventions, such as the trip to Hawaii, are among the
``people-to-people type'' exchanges that were ruled out.
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III had been criticized for
his travels, including a trip to a legal symposium with five other
department officials in Japan. Meese usually took commercial
flights.
   Runkel said Thornburgh would not have flown the 727 except that
another plane had broken down.
   But a letter from the Marshals Service, also an arm of the
Justice Department, said the jet had been requested six weeks
before the Hawaii trip, the Times reported.
   A unidentified FBI official told the Times that the Hawaii leg
of the trip cost $38,000. A first-class, round-trip ticket between
San Francisco and Honolulu costs about $1,400.
</TEXT>
