<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Uprising     10-07 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Uprising,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Bars Peace Group From Meeting With Palestinians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULKAREM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army Saturday barred 700
Israeli peace activists from entering an Arab town to talk with
Palestinians.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, Israeli troops shot and wounded
seven Palestinians, authorities said.
   At least 585 Palestinains have been killed and more than 12,000
wounded in the 21-month-old uprising against Israeli rule of the
occupied territories. Forty Israelis have died in the violence and
127 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs on suspicion of
cooperating with Israel.
   An army spokesman said the West Bank town of Tulkarem, where the
peace meeting was scheduled between Palestinians and the Israeli
activists, was a ``closed military area'' and that only residents
were permitted to enter.
   The spokesman, who could not be identified under standing
regulations, said Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin had refused to
grant permission to the left-wing Peace Now group to enter the
Palestinian town of about 50,000, 22 miles northeast of Tel Aviv.
He refused to elaborate.
   The peace activists, many waving banners reading ``Talk Peace
with the PLO Now,'' held a demonstration at roadblocks outside the
town. They were joined by two left-wing members of parliament and
Faisal Husseini, a leading Palestinian activist.
   ``We all know that Israelis could talk with Palestinians if the
roadblocks between us were removed,'' Husseini said.
   ``I want to tell you that we Palestinians have paid a heavy
price and will continue to do so until the forces of peace will
win,'' Husseini said in Arabic. His remarks were simultaneously
translated into Hebrew.
   Dedi Zucker, a left-wing legislator from the Citizens Rights
Movement, said: ``We must do all we can for peace now so we don't
have to attend funerals later.''
   Yael Dayan, daughter of Israeli war hero Moshe Dayan, greeted
Husseini and said she brought a message of peace.
   ``Husseini's father and my father fought each other in the
past,'' she said. ``I hope my childen and those of Husseini will
live together in peace.''
   Moshe Dayan served as defense minster during the 1967 Middle
East war, when Israel's armies seized the West Bank from Jordan and
the Gaza Strip from Egypt.
   Husseini's father, Abdel Qader, commanded a Palestinian force of
irregulars during the 1948 Middle East war. He was killed in a
battle for Jerusalem.
   After the demonstration a few leaders of Peace Now were able to
slip into Tulkarem, where they met with Mayor Hilmi Hanoun.
   The leaders, who asked not to be identified, quoted Hanoun as
saying: ``The moment a Palestinian state is born, we will have
peace.''
</TEXT>
