<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-07 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Drenches Parts of Texas, Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched San Antonio and parts of Florida, Kansas and
Nebraska on Saturday, and frost warnings were posted for much of
Indiana, Ohio and West Virginia.
   Morning frost reached from the northern Rockies to the upper
Mississippi Valley, with fair skies across the Ohio Valley.
   The cold spots in the Lower 48 states early Saturday were
Gunnison, Colo., and Grand Forks, N.D., with readings of 20 degrees.
   Rain caused flooding in parts of San Antonio, but much of the
flooding subsided by Saturday afternoon.
   Colder temperatures were forecast for the Ohio Valley by Sunday.
   Rainshowers and thunderstorms spanned southeast Texas, eastern
Florida, western Kansas, eastern Nebraska and northern Maine.
   San Antonio received 3 inches of rain during the six hours that
ended at 2 p.m. EDT. Tallahassee, Fla., received one-third of an
inch during that period.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Houghton, Mich., to 95 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.,
and Thermal, Calif.
</TEXT>
