<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 1810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-VaGovernor     10-07 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Governor,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Governor's Race Draws Well-Known Contributors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $20 million campaign for governor of
Virginia has produced a ``Who's Who'' list of celebrity givers,
from entertainer Bill Cosby to former White House Chief of Staff
Donald Regan.
   Even some news media names are listed on campaign finance
reports of those who have pumped money into the race between
Democrat L. Douglas Wilder, the state's lieutenant governor, and
Republican J. Marshall Coleman, a former Virginia attorney general.
   One is Ed Bradley of the CBS News program ``60 Minutes,'' who
gave $500 to Wilder in his bid to become the nation's first elected
black governor.
   ``I look upon this as part of my life as a private citizen,''
said Bradley, who met Wilder at a fund-raiser in New York ``and
liked what he had to say.''
   Bradley said he has contributed to other candidates and, while
has had some concerns about the potential conflict in reporting the
news and giving money to political campaigns, ``the alternative is
to do nothing.''
   ``I don't advertise it, but I don't hide it,'' he said. ``It's a
delicate line you tread.''
   When it comes to drawing money from the famous, Wilder has more
names than Coleman. Most of the gifts are small, with the exception
of Cosby, who gave $100,000 to Wilder.
   But other well-known contributors to the Democrat's campaign
have given far less. They include singer Barbra Streisand, who gave
$1,000; former tennis star Arthur Ashe Jr., like Wilder a Richmond
native, who gave $3,000; and Charlayne Hunter Gault, of the
MacNeil-Lehrer Newshour on public broadcasting stations, who gave
$700.
   Coleman's most famous contributors are political celebrities
rather than entertainers or media stars.
   In addition to Regan, a top aide to former President Reagan, who
gave $10,000, they include President Bush's son, Marvin, who
contributed $1,000 to the GOP candidate's campaign.
   The two campaigns, meantime, also have backing from well-known
national corporations. A major tobacco industry player sided with
Coleman, while Wilder tapped some beer money.
   New York-based Philip Morris USA, which has a major cigarette
manufacturing plant in Richmond, put $15,000 into Coleman's war
chest.
   The Miller Brewing Co. of Milwaukee gave $250 to Wilder. Miller
has a brewery just across the Virginia line in Eden, N.C.
   Wilder also got $7,500 from the Southland Corp. of Dallas, whose
7-Eleven stores are known coast-to-coast.
   In at least one case, a corporate giver is playing it safe by
contributing to both camps. The Richmond-based CSX Corp., a
railroad holding company, has given about $30,000 each to Coleman
and Wilder.
   In all, Coleman has raised $8.2 million to $4.8 million for
Wilder.
   Adding the fund-raising of Coleman's GOP primary opponents and
Wilder's only opponent for the Democratic nomination, state Sen.
Daniel W. Bird Jr. of Wytheville, brings the total for the
governor's race to about $20 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
