<HEAD>Workers Strike Two San Francisco Hotels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 700 workers struck the Hyatt
Regency and Hyatt Union Square hotels Saturday in a dispute over
wages and fringe benefits, said union and hotel authorities.
   The two facilities ``are continuing to operate _ certainly no
problems,'' said Hyatt attorney Lisa Van Krieken.
   The strike took the hotels by surprise, she said, adding that a
negotiating session was set for Monday.
   Striking workers include dishwashers, cooks, janitors, waiters,
bartenders, maids, busboys and telephone operators.
   ``The Hyatts have refused even to discuss our bargaining
proposals,'' said Sherri Chiesa, president of Local 2 of the Hotel
and Restaurant Employees and Bartenders Union. The sides were ``far
apart on many issues,'' she said.
   The union office said more than 700 employees were involved in
the strike, which started at 6 a.m.
   The striking employees have been working without a contract
since Aug. 15. They voted Sept. 26 to authorize the union's
leadership to call a strike.
