<FIRST>u a AM-IowaCrash-Teen     10-07 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Crash-Teen,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Parts Search Pays Off for Teen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aviation disaster is turning into a
windfall for a northwest Iowa family.
   Glen Galvin, 17, has earned $6,700 in rewards in his search for
parts from a disintegrated engine from a jumbo jet that crashed
this summer.
   ``It's kind of like winning the lottery, only the odds are
better,'' said Galvin, a senior at Alta High School.
   The engine pieces are from a United Airlines DC-10 that was
headed to Chicago from Denver when its No. 2 engine broke apart on
July 19.
   As the shredded engine parts fell over northwest Iowa, they
severed hydraulic lines in the plane, crippling the flight
controls. Pilots were able to bring the disabled plane to the
airport at Sioux City where it crashed on landing.
   The crash claimed 112 lives, but 184 people survived.
   Most of the parts found so far appear to be engine fan blades or
pieces of blades, said Stephen Gadd, a lawyer representing General
Electric Co. The company made the CF6-6 tail engine that
disintegrated before the crash.
   Still missing is the 300-pound titanium disk that held the
blades. The company is offering $278,000 in rewards for the parts,
ranging from a $500 minimum to $50,000 for the disk, Gadd said.
   They are offering the rewards in hopes the parts will provide
clues to the cause of the crash.
   Galvin didn't begin looking for parts until the National Guard
completed its search of corn and soybean fields in the area.
   ``I found one of the first-stage (engine) pieces right away and
that pretty much started it,'' said Galvin. A search over the Labor
Day weekend turned up most of his ``first batch'' of parts, he
said. He found them in a pasture where he was riding his motor bike.
   The first group of five engine parts netted him $3,200 in
rewards.
   Jerome Clark, a representative of GE Aerospace Engines,
inspected the newer parts in Galvin's possession Thursday and said
several will net the teen-ager another reward in the amount of
$3,500.
   Galvin hasn't decided what he will do with his share of the
reward, but his mother, Illa Glavin, has some ideas.
   ``We figure 10 percent will go to the church and then we are
going to divide it among the family members,'' she said. ``I think
cars or maybe a computer; we look at it as a windfall.''
</TEXT>
