<FIRST>r a AM-Boeing     10-07 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Negotiations Scheduled in Boeing Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal mediator said he's ready to organize
new talks between the Boeing Co. and striking Machinists, but there
was no indication Saturday that negotiations would occur soon.
   Labor leaders planned a regional strategy session on Monday,
while striking workers took vacations or temporary jobs as the
strike moved through its fourth day.
   ``We're going to remain open and ready to do whatever we can to
settle the situation at the right time,'' Boeing spokesman Paul
Binder said Saturday. ``We have not at this point planned for any
meetings, scheduled any meetings or made any contact with (federal
mediator) Doug Hammond.''
   Both Boeing and the union say they are willing to negotiate, but
Hammond has declined to say who or what was holding things up.
   ``I have heard from the union, and they are interested in
returning to the table,'' Hammond said Friday, ``but nothing is
scheduled, and I don't foresee anything this weekend.''
   In a recorded message at his office Saturday, Hammond said, ``At
this time there are no meetings scheduled in the Boeing labor
dispute. If there is any change in this, an announcement will be
made.''
   Spokesmen for the Machinists were out of their offices Saturday
morning and not available for comment.
   The strike began Wednesday for 43,300 workers in the Seattle
area, 12,000 in Wichita, Kan., 1,700 in Portland, Ore., and others
at several locations nationwide.
   The machinists voted by 85 percent Tuesday to reject an offer
that included an immediate raise of 4 percent with 3 percent raises
in both 1990 and 1991, annual bonuses of 8 percent of a worker's
gross earnings this year and 3 percent the next plus a reduction in
mandatory overtime. The offer also included a cost-of-living
formula to account for virtually all inflation.
   Picket lines remained up and supervisory personnel continued to
fill in as they could on production lines, Binder said, although he
had no figures on how many people were working.
</TEXT>
