<FIRST>r i AM-NATO-Soviet     10-07 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Soviet,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet General Speaks To Assembly Of NATO Legislators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet general made an unprecedented
appearance Saturday before an assembly of NATO legislators, touting
the Kremlin's unilateral arms cuts and challenging the West to act
on disarmament.
   ``This is a great honor for me, the Warsaw pact and the Soviet
military. This is a historic moment. I am here, even in uniform,
representing the Warsaw Pact,'' said Gen. Vladimir Lobov, the first
deputy chief of staff of the Soviet General Staff.
   Lobov, along with NATO supreme commander Gen. John Galvin, spoke
to the Defense and Security Committee of the North Atlantic
Assembly, a consultative group of legislators from member nations
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   ``The Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact are no longer a threat to
NATO, to the NATO states and certainly not to the United States,''
said Lobov, who is also a member of the Soviet legislature.
   He said the Soviet Union has decided unilaterally to reduce its
forces by 500,000 troops, 10,000 tanks and 8,500 warplanes. He said
the Soviets will withdraw three armored divisions from East Germany
and remove 500 nuclear warheads from the territories of its Warsaw
Pact allies by the end of the year.
   ``What are you doing?'' Lobov asked the legislators. ``We are
not just talking about things, we are doing them. And of course, we
are expecting something from you.''
   Galvin said that despite the reductions, ``the Soviet Union
remains the most powerful military force in the world. ... They
will have to reduce a long way before things are brought into
balance.
   ``It is the conventional imbalance that poses the greatest
threat to security in Europe,'' he added.
   The NATO commander suggested the Soviets should take several
steps at conventional arms reductions talks in Vienna to raise
Western confidence.
   Galvin said the Soviets should agree to remove their
quick-strike capability by cuts in first-echelon forces in Eastern
Europe; dismantle supply depots in forward areas; remove
operational maneuver groups and high-readiness forces from forward
areas; slow conventional arms production; agree to verification
procedures; and sign a pact to make the measures binding.
   ``Intentions can change,'' Galvin cautioned.
</TEXT>
