<DOCNO> AP891007-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-07-89 1911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Spending-Taxes     10-07 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending-Taxes,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration in Closed-Door Talks Seeking Cut in Capital Gains
Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top aides to President Bush met with Senate
leaders behind closed doors Saturday in an effort to devise a
strategy for winning a cut in capital gains taxes without delaying
critical deficit-reduction legislation.
   Democratic leaders, who oppose the capital gains legislation,
were looking for a way to pass the deficit-reduction bill without
the tax cut.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, announced
that seven hours of meetings had produced no agreement.
Nevertheless, he said, he and Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas
``believe that the prospects for such an agreement are sufficiently
encouraging to commit that we will continue our meetings.''
   The next round of negotiations was scheduled Sunday morning.
   The central question is whether Republicans will be able to add
a capital gains cut to the bill by a simple majority vote _ 51 at
most _ or whether they will have to get 60 votes because of rules
that govern consideration of the deficit bill.
   The House bill already includes a capital gains cut.
   Each side set the groundwork for blaming the other if the
negotiations fail. Failure could mean further delay in passage of a
catchall package of deficit reduction _ known as reconciliation _
and lead to automatic, across-the-board cuts in federal spending on
Oct. 16.
   Mitchell told reporters the White House is closely involved in
the discussions. ``Our primary objective is ... a meaningful
deficit-reduction package,'' he said. ``The difference we have in
this discussion is that the primary objective of the administration
is a capital-gains tax cut.''
   Dole said of the Democrats: ``They've got a problem. They are
going to be blamed for ... (the automatic budget cuts) and they've
got to get out of it.''
   Mitchell met with Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the
Finance Committee, and Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the
Budget Committee. House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., attended
briefly.
   Trying to develop GOP strategy with Dole were Sens. Pete
Domenici of New Mexico and Bob Packwood of Oregon, senior
Republicans on, respectively, the Budget and Finance committees.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and White House budget
director Richard G. Darman led the administration effort.
   The stated purpose of the meetings is to find a way to strip
from the deficit-reduction bill _ a package of revenue increases
and spending cuts _ that are not directly related to reducing the
deficit. The measure has become so weighted down with extraneous
pet projects that there is little likelihood that Congress can
enact it before the Oct. 16 deadline.
   The chief controversy is over Bush's proposal to cut taxes on
capital gains. The measure is part of the House version of the bill
and Republicans want to add it to the Senate version.
   Democratic leaders in the Senate are countering with an
amendment to eliminate the capital gains cut and substitute an
expansion of tax-deductible Individual Retirement Accounts.
   Republicans insist that if every extraneous item is stripped
from the bill _ and they don't concede that capital gains is
extraneous _ they be assured a separate vote on capital gains. That
would leave them an easier path to passage with just a simple
majority.
   But Mitchell was emphatic that Democrats, who control the
Senate, will not waive any Senate rules to make it easier for
Republicans to duplicate the capital gains victory they took in the
House. ``That will not happen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
