<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0586 10-07 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Barco Government Was Negotiating with Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Montoya's denial. Pickup
graf 11 pvs `According to....' DROPS last three grafs to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco's government
was trying to negotiate a truce with drug traffickers until a
presidential candidate was assassinated in August, a newspaper said
Saturday.
   However, the president's secretary general, German Montoya,
denied he had talked to drug traffickers and said the Barco
administration had never wavered in its commitment to fight the
drug cartels.
   He made the comments after the Bogata daily, La Prensa, said a
former ambassador to the United Nations had delivered messages
between Montoya and the drug dealers. It said Montoya had acted on
direct orders from the president in the negotiations.
   In four years leading up to the purported negotiations, drug
traffickers killed a justice minister, an attorney general, a
newspaper publisher and scores of other people.
   Barco's administration began an unprecedented crackdown on the
nation's drug cartels after Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a presidential
candidate, was killed while addressing a campaign rally on Aug. 18.
   Two of La Prensa's main owners are Misael Pastrana and Belesario
Betancur, both former presidents and members of the opposition
Conservative Party. Barco is a member of the Liberal Party.
   La Prensa said it had documents from Sen. Alvaro Leyva Duran,
also of the Conservative Party, showing that Montoya wanted talks
to be held between the drug traffickers on one side and the
Colombian government and the United States on the other.
   The drug lords reportedly were prepared to contract former U.S.
Secretary of State Henry Kissenger's Washington-based lobbying firm
to persuade the United States government to begin a dialogue,
according to the newspaper.
   La Prensa said U.S. participation never developed because of
strong opposition first by the Reagan administration and then the
Bush administration.
   In his sharply worded denial Montoya said, ``The decision of the
government was and is to make sure that all the law's weight falls
on those common criminals and terrorists.''
   His statement called the La Prensa report ``calumnious'' and
said it showed the paper's ``lack of solidarity with the national
crusade against drug traffickers that is led by the government and
supported by the world.''
   He acknowledged meeting with a former U.N. ambassador and
interior minister, Joaquin Vallejo, but he said he did so on his
own authority and told him there could be no talks with drug
traffickers.
   According to La Prensa, Vallejo carried messages from the
Medellin drug cartel starting in September 1988 and up until five
days after the assassination of Galan, the leading candidate for
the Liberal Party's nomination for presidential elections in March.
   Authorities blamed drug traffickers for the murder.
   At a meeting on Aug. 23, three days after Galan's burial,
Montoya told Vallejo that negotiations with traffickers were no
longer possible because the government had decided to declare
``total war,'' La Prensa said.
   Barco began his declared war against traffickers on Aug. 19,
saying he would extradite traffickers wanted in the United States.
   The traffickers responded with a terrorist bombing campaign,
which officials say is aimed at forcing the government into new
talks.
   The Barco administration has said repeatedly since Galan's death
that it will never agree to talks with drug lords responsible for
slaying scores of the country's political leaders, police and army
officials, and judges.
   La Prensa said the main document among the messages is a memo in
Vallejo's handwriting that summarizes proposals from Group A,
identified as the Medellin cartel. La Prensa published a photograph
of the piece of paper.
   According to the copy, the cartel was ready to abandon the
cocaine processing business, turn over its arms, laboratories and
airstrips and help the government fight other drug traffickers. In
return, the traffickers asked for amnesty and guarantees not to be
extradited.
   The three alleged chiefs of the cartel, Jorge Luis Ochoa, Pablo
Escobar and Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, are among the 12 Colombian
traffickers most wanted for extradition to the United States.
   The Colombian government has offered a $250,000 reward for
information leading to the capture of Escobar and Rodriguez.
   U.S. officials say the Medellin cartel and a rival trafficking
group based in the southern city of Cali are responsible for
processing 80 percent of the cocaine sold on U.S. streets.
</TEXT>
