<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     10-07 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Men Die in East Texas Airplane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNCERTAIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine airplane plowed into a
pine tree and exploded shortly after taking off in heavy fog from
an east Texas airstrip, killing all five people aboard, officials
said.
   The five men were headed to Destin, Fla., on vacation Friday
night, said Lt. Frank Garrett of the Harrison County Sheriff's
Department.
   Samuel F. Vaughn III, president of Marshall-based Winchester
Oil, owned the airplane and airstrip and was taking friends to
Florida to go fishing, officials said.
   The cause of the crash was not immediately known, Garrett said.
But he said the pilot of the six-seater Cessna-208 turboprop,
Steven Engelbrecht, may not have realized how low to the ground he
was, due to the heavy fog.
   ``The visibility was about 50 to 60 feet,'' Garrett said. ``It
appears the pilot took off and began his left turn too soon because
the airplane crashed in some trees about 150 feet from the runway.''
   Federal Aviation Administration officials were investigating the
accident on Saturday, Garrett said.
   The other victims were identified as Chase Staggers, 29; Johnny
Johnson, 29; and David Perkins, 28, all of Marshall.
   Uncertain is about 20 miles northeast of Marshall, near the
Louisiana border.
</TEXT>
