<FIRST>r a AM-Panama-Poll     10-07 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Poll,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newsweek: Most Americans Think Noriega Should Step Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans think Gen. Manuel Noriega should
give up power in Panama yet a majority oppose the use of U.S.
military forces to overthrow him, according to a Newsweek poll
released Saturday.
   The poll found that 45 percent of Americans approve of the
degree of U.S. involvement in Tuesday's attempted coup against
Noriega. And nearly three in four expressed a ``fair amount'' or a
``great deal'' of confidence in President Bush's ability to handle
the current situation in Panama as effectively as possible.
   But 30 percent of those polled said the U.S. did not play enough
of a role in the reported coup.
   The poll indicated that Americans strongly support persuading
Panama's neighboring nations to pressure Noriega to surrender
power, with 76 percent of respondents favoring this approach. It
was the most popular of four options for U.S. policy toward Panama
offered by the poll.
   More than half supported imposing a total U.S. economic boycott
on Panama and 46 percent favored setting up a secret operation to
unseat Noriega. Only 26 percent favored use of U.S. military forces
to invade Panama and overthrow Noriega.
   The Gallup Organization interviewed a national sample of 750
adults by telephone on Oct. 5 and 6 for this poll. The margin of
error is plus or minus 4 percent.
</TEXT>
