<FIRST>r i AM-Morocco-Rebels     10-07 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morocco-Rebels,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Attack Ignites Heaviest Fighting in Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polisario rebels in the disputed Western
Sahara attacked a Moroccan defense line Saturday, setting off the
bloodiest battle since the two sides declared a truce in February.
   The government said 14 of its soldiers were killed and 80 rebels
killed or wounded.
   A Polisario statement, which described the battle as ``murderous
violence,'' said the fighting broke out at dawn and lasted four
hours.
   The statement, issued in Algeria, Algiers, claimed its fighters
breached nine miles of Morocco's defensive front and pushed
government forces back 15 miles.
   The rebels did not say how the battle ended or give casualty
figures. It said ``numerous'' government soldiers forces were
killed, wounded or taken prisoner.
   The government reported that in addition to the 14 soldiers
killed 31 troopers were wounded. It also said four rebels were
taken prisoner.
   It claimed its forces repelled the attack launched south of the
town of Guelta Zemmour from Mauritanian territory.
   The government said its troops captured 10 jeeps armed with
missile launchers and anti-tank rockets, and 12 Polisario vehicles
were destroyed by Moroccan air attacks.
   The Western Sahara has been claimed by Morocco since Spain left
the territory in 1975, but the Polisario has proclaimed it an
independent state.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar has proposed a
plan to hold a referendum in the mineral-rich region.
   The Polisasrio guerrilla movement, once actively supported by
Algeria, has fought a mainly losing battle against about 100,000
Moroccan troops in the area.
   The Sahara front had been quiet, except for isolated Polisario
attacks, since the guerrillas declared a ``temporary truce'' in
February following King Hassan II's meeting with Polisario leaders
in Marrakech.
   Similar meetings had been scheduled but were canceled by the
king, who called them ``pointless.''
</TEXT>
