<FIRST>r a AM-RottenSneakers     10-07 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rotten Sneakers,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foul Feet Compete in Rotten Sneaker Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sweet smell of success soured in this
northeast Ohio town, where a 12-year-old girl won the regional
finals in the International Rotten Sneaker Contest on Saturday.
   Melissa Bergdorf, a seventh grader, was the winner _ if that's
the word for it _ with a pair of high-top tennis shoes twice
rescued from the trash can.
   ``They just keep coming back,'' said her mother, Delmarie
Carbaugh, from the Akron suburb of Uniontown.
   Melissa's shoes, without toes and with melted soles, were nearly
done in on camping trips, Mrs. Carbaugh said.
   ``There's not much left. ... The bottom is melted from walking
on hot bricks and the toes are totally gone,'' she said.
   Melissa will be sent to Montpelier, Vt., for the international
contest in March. Her mother, who was awarded the Purple Sole _ an
Odor-Eater shoe insert on a purple silk ribbon _ plans to accompany
her.
   The contest's 17 participants ranging in age from 8 to 16 had to
first prove the foul footwear was their own by skipping in place
and jumping rope.
   The shoes' tattered, shabby appearance were factors, but key to
victory was their smell, said David Hazlett, operations manager for
Eastwood Drug store, where the contest was held. The five judges
were a mother, a pharmacist and a coach; a sales manager from
national sponsor and manufacturer of Odor-Eaters, Combe Inc. of
White Plains, N.Y.; and a dog named Frankie.
</TEXT>
