<FIRST>r a AM-RobinHoodEmbezzler     10-07 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robin Hood Embezzler,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Emptied Credit Union Till To Help Poor, Laywer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINTE A LA HACHE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who took more than
$242,000 from a church-sponsored credit union gave all the cash to
the poor, her lawyer said.
   Vergie Encalade, former manager of the St. Thomas Parish Federal
Credit Union, is facing a federal indictment that accuses her of
siphoning off the money from October 1984 to August 1989.
   ``It's sort of hard for even her to explain,'' her lawyer,
William Quigley, said Friday. ``All the money was given to needy
people and institutions, from starving children in Ethiopia to the
Little Sisters of the Poor.''
   ``There's no evidence she or her family benefited from one cent
of that money,'' Quigley said. ``She's going to accept the
responsibility for what happened and take whatever punishment the
court feels appropriate.''
   A spokesman for the Louisiana Credit Union League said the
accounts of all 350 members are covered by insurance.
   If convicted, Encalade faces up to five years in prison, said
First Assistant U.S. Attorney Al Winters. Encalade is to turn
herself in next week to be arraigned, he said.
   Encalade is known in Plaquemines Parish as an outspoken,
sometimes strident activist who has had a number of run-ins with
public officials in her fight for equal rights and employment
opportunities for blacks.
   In 1986, Encalade and her husband, Justice of the Peace
Frederick Encalade, were convicted of disturbing the peace after
leading 30 people into a Plaquemines Parish Council meeting. The
group disrupted the meeting after the council refused to discuss
setting up a task force on unemployment.
   Quigley said Encalade managed to escape detection during a
number of federal audits. He said she ultimately went to
authorities and confessed.
</TEXT>
