<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     10-07 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Step Up Attackss In Rural Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels launched five attacks against
government troops in rural provinces, killing four soldiers and
wounding eight, the Defense Ministry said Saturday.
   It said the attacks occurred Friday in provinces north and east
of Managua. The statement did not mention rebel casualties.
   Rebels, known as Contras, killed six government soldiers in an
early morning attack Wednesday on a rural military outpost.
   Five Central American presidents signed an agreement in August
designed to end the war and repatriate the Contras, most of whom
are in bases in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border. In return the
Sandinista government promised to hold fair elections.
   Some Contras have returned to Nicaragua, saying they plan to
participate in the elections set for February, but others rejected
the peace plan and said they will continue fighting.
   Observers from the Organization of American States have limited
their movements because of the clashes. There are 52 OAS observers
in Nicaragua to oversee compliance with the peace accords.
   The Contras have been fighting the left-wing Sandinistas since
1981. They claim the Sandinistas' shift to the far left betrayed
the revolution that ousted conservative President Anastasio Somoza
in 1979, ending 42 years of rule by the Somoza family.
</TEXT>
