<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     10-07 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Resigns To Pave Way For Elections; Papandreou Accepts Mandate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Premier Tzannis Tzannetakis
resigned Saturday, saying his government's mission of starting a
cleanup of Greece's politics was fulfilled. Elections are expected
to be held for next month.
   Former socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou, whose
scandal-plagued government was replaced three months ago by
Tzannetakis' administration, said he accepted a presidential
mandate to try to form a Cabinet within three days.
   Tzannetakis said President Christos Sartzetakis accepted his
resignation but he agreed to stay on as caretaker until a new
Cabinet is appointed.
   He told reporters that during his 45-minute meeting with
Sartzetakis at the presidential palace he explained that his
right-left coalition government completed its task of launching
legal action against officials of the former socialist
administration.
   Within two hours Sartzetakis called in conservative New
Democracy Party leader Constantine Mitsotakis to ask him to attempt
to form a government. But the 71-year-old politician, confident of
victory at the polls, rejected the mandate and recommended that
procedures be hastened for the formation of a government to conduct
elections on Nov. 5.
   He was followed by Papandreou, whose Panhellenic Socialist
Movement (PASOK) lost the June 18 elections after eight years in
office.
   Papandreou told reporters as he left the palace that he had
accepted the presidential mandate. But it appeared highly unlikely
he could put together an administration by Monday that would win
Parliament's confidence.
   Mitsotakis said earlier that ``it would lack seriousness for
Papandreou to take the mandate and move around like a beggar since
he knows one way or another that he has no margins to achieve any
political result.''
   Papandreou said Mitsotakis' comment ``insulted the democratic
institutions and the country's political life.''
   If all attempts to form another government fails, Sartzetakis
then appoints a caretaker regime to take the country to elections.
   In the June election, New Democracy won 145 seats in the
300-member unicameral parliament. PASOK took 125 places while the
Coalition of the Left and Progress copped 28 seats. Two remaining
seats went to independents.
   New Democracy had joined in an unprecedented alliance with the
Communist-dominated Coalition of the Left and Progress to keep
Papandreou from retaining power and punish corrupt PASOK officials.
   Parliament has twice remanded the 70-year-old Papandreou in the
past three weeks to special courts where he will be tried for his
alleged involvement in a multimillion dollar bank scandal and for
allegedly instigating illegal wiretapping of his political friends
and foes while he was in office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
