<FIRST>r a AM-GaySymposium     10-07 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Symposium,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Say Conference is `Gay-Bashing'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights activists stormed a hotel on
Saturday to protest a conservative church group symposium where
speakers warned that homosexuals are a threat to American culture.
   About 35 activists chanted and blew whistles as they entered the
lobby of the Pan Pacific Hotel. The protest occured about a half
hour before the day's keynote speech was set to be delivered.
   The speech by William B. Allen, chairman of the U.S. Commission
on Civil Rights, was titled ``Blacks, Animals, and Homosexuals:
What is a Minority?''
   The protesters sat on the floor for less than an hour before
police wearing leather or surgical gloves led them away. No
immediate arrests were made.
   The sit-in was part of a larger demonstration at the hotel
against the West Coast Symposium on Homosexuality and Public Policy
Implications, held by the California Coalition for Traditional
Values, a church-formed organization.
   The approximate 200 demonstrators outnumbered the estimated 150
people attending the event.
   Allen's speech was delayed nearly four hours from its scheduled
noon delivery time. A conference organizer said his plane was
delayed in Monterey.
   On Friday, the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights, with Allen
dissenting, branded the title of the speech ``thoughtless,
disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory.''
   Allen told reporters after his speech that the title was ``as
innocent as can be,'' and blasted his colleagues for not reading
the prepared remarks.
   Allen won a standing ovation for the speech in which he opposed
anti-discrimination laws for specific ethnic or minority groups.
   ``Historically, that process has always led to heightened
tensions and heightened antagonisms among the groups competing for
the rewards of the society,'' he said.
   Such demands by blacks in the civil rights era spawned a similar
movement for animals, argued Allen, who is black.
   ``Express laws for minority groups ... is the beginning of the
evil of reducing American blacks to an equality with animals, and
then seducing other groups (including homosexuals) to seek the same
charitable treatment,'' he said.
   ``Basically, what is going on in here is gay-bashing,'' said
Kevin Farrell, of the Orange County Visibility League, a homosexual
rights group with about 300 members.
   ``What's dangerous here is the thin veneer of respectability,''
Farrell said outside the hotel in this Orange County city, 25 miles
southeast of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
