<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     10-07 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Diplomat Visits Panamanian Opposition Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief U.S. diplomat in Panama on
Saturday visited opposition leader Guillermo Endara at the papal
envoy's residence, where Endara fled after government soldiers beat
him at his office two days earlier.
   Also Saturday, authorities rounded up 10 opposition party
members from their homes and told them to end political activities
before releasing them, the party said.
   Endara was visited at the papal nuncio's residence by John
Maisto, the U.S. charge d'affaires. Maisto made no statement after
his visit.
   Endara was in the 18th day of a hunger strike to protest the
rule of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the Defense Forces chief who
controls the government.
   The opposition leader was attacked and forced from his office by
Noriega's soldiers during a crackdown in the wake of last week's
failed military coup to overthrow Noriega.
   Noriega has accused U.S. officials of backing Tuesday's
attempted coup. U.S. forces blocked some roads but did not take
part in fighting.
   Congressional investigators were expected in Panama City within
the next few days to determine the role the U.S. played in the
coup, sources said Saturday.
   The planned visit was reported by Panamanian opposition
officials as well as U.S. diplomats and military spokesmen. They
spoke on condition of anonymity. Among those expected was Rep. John
Murtha, D-Pa. He was in Panama as an observer of the May 7
elections, which the government annulled after international
observers said the ticket led by Endara won by a 3-1 margin.
   Congressional critics say the Bush administration should have
strongly backed last week's uprising, which appeared to have the
support of some members of Noriega's High Command.
   In Washington, officials said Saturday that President Bush was
weighing more economic sanctions against Panama and sounding out
members of congressional intelligence committees on covert actions
against Noriega.
   The United States has used political and economic pressure in an
effort to oust Noriega since February 1988, when he was indicted in
Florida on drug- trafficking charges.
   In his crackdown since the failed coup, Noriega has arrested
dozens of soldiers and political figures, taken radio stations off
the air and prepared to impose emergency laws to deal with dissent,
including plans to fire employees viewed as disloyal.
   The members of the opposition Christian Democratic Party were
rounded up at their homes Saturday and taken to regional Defense
Forces headquarters in the city of Herrera, 120 miles west of
Panama, according to party Secretary General Ivan Romero.
   The area party members were told to halt all political
activities, including distributing political ``propaganda'' and
holding meetings. They were also warned ``to stop making phone
calls to Panama City,'' he said.
   They were then released.
   Endara leads the Civil Democratic Opposition Alliance, an
opposition coalition that includes the Christian Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
