<FIRST>r a AM-PhonyPanamanian     10-07 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phony Panamanian,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Poses as Anti-Noriega Leader, Fools News Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man in a fake mustache, glasses and a phony
accent made the evening news by posing as the spokesman for local
Panamanians opposed to that nation's leader Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   Kurt Rappaport, 22, is a University of Southern California
graduate and son of a lawyer. But viewers who watched the news on
KTTV last Tuesday saw him as Arturo Valdez, chairman of the
nonexistent USA-Panama Friendship Council.
   In a 10-second segment, Rappaport told an interviewer in broken
English that the Southern California Panamanian community was
willing to send ``money, forces _ anything with help from the
United States'' to fight Noriega.
   ``They see right through him, like a clear curtain,'' Rappaport
said.
   Rolando Santos, KTTV's director of news operations, confirmed on
Friday that the station had been hoaxed.
   ``Basically, if you look at the situation, somebody played a
prank on us,'' Santos said. ``We're trying to track down what
happened right now. Obviously, it was not intentional.''
   The news staff followed proper procedures, including calling
officials in Washington D.C., he said.
   Rappaport said the impersonation began on a whim last Tuesday
afternoon when a woman identifying herself as a representative of
the KTTV assignment desk called his home in Beverly Hills.
   The woman asked if she had reached the Panamanian consulate.
Rappaport replied that she had, but no officials were available to
talk. He took down a telephone number and called back a few minutes
later as Arturo Valdez.
   ``I'd just finished playing tennis and I had to take a shower,
put on a suit and tie,'' he said. ``I dug out an old pair of
glasses, but I had to shop around for the mustache.''
   The mustache was slightly askew when he arrived at the Fox TV
studio, so Rappaport declined pancake makeup, exclaiming: ``No! I
am not here to be beautiful. I am here to speak for my country.''
   After the interview, Rappaport discovered that the Panamanian
consulate in Los Angeles had closed Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
