<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Racism     10-07 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Racism,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italians and Immigrants Rally Against Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people marched through rainy
city streets Saturday to protest racism and demand better
conditions for Italy's immigrants.
   Under an intermittent drizzle, the marchers walked through
central Rome behind several African immigrants carrying a banner
reading: ``Together for a future without racism.''
   Organizers said 200,000 people took part, but police estimates
varied from 60,000 to 100,000.
   The march was organized by the Communist labor union CGIL and
dozens of citizens' groups and labor associations.
   Demonstrators called for legislation to improve conditions for
immigrants.
   The demonstration was organized afater the killing of a South
African refugee in southern Italy. The death of the migrant farm
worker at the hands of robbers brought demands for improved living
conditions for immigrants.
   In recent years thousands of immigrants from African and other
Third World countries have come to Italy in search of jobs. Very
few are legally registered and most work for low wages.
   The increase in illegal immigration has sparked occasional
racist outbursts among some Italians.
</TEXT>
