<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-IAPA     10-07 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-IAPA,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Covering Drug Trafficking Is IAPA Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Should journalists risk their lives to
report on drug trafficking?
   About 500 members of the Inter-American Press Association will
discuss that and other topics at this week's annual IAPA gathering
beginning Sunday.
   ``We've put the Colombian publishers in the limelight because of
the issues at stake there,'' said Alejandro Junco de la Vega,
executive director of the Monterrey newspaper El Norte, host of the
meeting.
   Luis Gabriel Cano of the Colombian newspaper El Espectador, the
target of a recent bombing blamed on narcotics traffickers, will
lead a panel discussion about the war between drug lords and the
government in his country.
   ``What should the behavior of the press be when you're risking
your life and your company to write about drugs?'' Junco said in a
interview.
   ``It's a growing problem for Mexican newspapers because Mexico
has been converted into a highway for the trafficking of Colombian
drugs from the fields to the United States,'' he said.
   Monterrey, about 150 miles south of the Texas border, is
northern Mexico's largest city with nearly 3 million people.
   IAPA has about 1,300 members throughout the United States, Latin
America, Canada and the Caribbean.
   Manuel Jimenez, IAPA president, said newspapers need to improve
coverage of drug barons.
   ``The work of the press is to bring them to the surface, to
unmask them. We're not doing it sufficiently well,'' Jimenez said
on his arrival Friday.
   Also to be discussed is the progress of press freedoms,
especially in Latin America, said Jimenez of the daily newspaper La
Nacion in Costa Rica.
   The official program begins Sunday night and Mexican President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari will address the members on Monday. The
meeting lasts through Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
